WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.980 --> 00:00:09.970
My name is Robin Kelsey, and
I'm Dean of Arts and Humanities

00:00:09.970 --> 00:00:13.300
and a professor in the History
of Art and Architecture

00:00:13.300 --> 00:00:13.990
Department.

00:00:13.990 --> 00:00:16.870
And it is my great
pleasure to welcome you

00:00:16.870 --> 00:00:21.310
all here this evening.

00:00:21.310 --> 00:00:28.330
Because we have two authors with
us, two books, much to discuss,

00:00:28.330 --> 00:00:31.120
I'm going to keep my opening
remarks and my introductions

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:35.540
of the speakers
very, very brief.

00:00:35.540 --> 00:00:37.270
I would just say
that in recent years

00:00:37.270 --> 00:00:41.320
it has become clear that
one of the issues upon which

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:45.940
the humanities need to
train their attention

00:00:45.940 --> 00:00:51.040
is on the very
issue of attention.

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:55.330
As teachers, we are witnessing
a generational shift

00:00:55.330 --> 00:00:59.590
in the conditions of
attention, a shift

00:00:59.590 --> 00:01:05.950
riddled with societal anxiety
about failures of attention,

00:01:05.950 --> 00:01:09.100
about deficits and disorders.

00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:12.080
And at Harvard, we
have concentrations.

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:15.520
But really, who can concentrate?

00:01:15.520 --> 00:01:20.230
This evening, we will take some
time to talk about distraction.

00:01:20.230 --> 00:01:25.970
I think it's the perfect
end-of-semester topic.

00:01:25.970 --> 00:01:29.140
Those of you who have been good
enough to join us this evening

00:01:29.140 --> 00:01:34.690
can hardly be asked to give your
full attention to this event.

00:01:34.690 --> 00:01:39.460
You should give whatever
fraction seems right to you.

00:01:39.460 --> 00:01:42.400
Hewing to the spirit
of this topic,

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:45.040
our conversation
may wend and wander.

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:48.130
It can dive a gate
down cul-de-sacs,

00:01:48.130 --> 00:01:51.250
or drift off into reverie.

00:01:51.250 --> 00:01:56.170
Very excited-- at least
part of me is anyway.

00:01:56.170 --> 00:01:58.990
So we have two wonderful
scholars with us this evening

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:04.310
to help us to come to terms
with our inconstant attentions.

00:02:04.310 --> 00:02:06.430
I'm going to
introduce them both,

00:02:06.430 --> 00:02:08.470
and then each will
come up in turn

00:02:08.470 --> 00:02:12.460
to talk about their
most recent book, which

00:02:12.460 --> 00:02:17.870
is in one manner or another
addressing the topic at hand.

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:21.490
So I'm going to start with
Marina Van Zuylen, who

00:02:21.490 --> 00:02:24.160
joins us from Bard College.

00:02:24.160 --> 00:02:27.790
Marina is Professor of French
and Comparative Literature

00:02:27.790 --> 00:02:33.040
at Bard, and also serves as
the national academic director

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:36.350
of the Clemente Course
in the Humanities,

00:02:36.350 --> 00:02:40.900
a program with which some
of you may be familiar.

00:02:40.900 --> 00:02:44.290
It's an amazing program
that brings the humanities

00:02:44.290 --> 00:02:48.070
to low-income adults.

00:02:48.070 --> 00:02:51.130
Barack Obama has already
thanked her personally

00:02:51.130 --> 00:02:52.280
for this service.

00:02:52.280 --> 00:02:57.610
But I think we should add our
own gratitude on this occasion.

00:02:57.610 --> 00:03:01.240
She is the author of a lovely
new small volume entitled

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:03.580
The Plenitude of Distraction.

00:03:03.580 --> 00:03:06.040
And indeed there is a
plenitude of thinking in it,

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:10.720
despite its very handy size.

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:14.680
She is also the author of
two wonderful other books--

00:03:14.680 --> 00:03:17.620
Difficulty as an
Aesthetic Principle--

00:03:17.620 --> 00:03:21.340
Realism and Unreadability
in Stifter, Melville,

00:03:21.340 --> 00:03:24.910
and Flaubert; and a book
I particularly love--

00:03:24.910 --> 00:03:28.000
Monomania-- the Flight
from Everyday Life

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:31.780
in Literature and Art.

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:35.680
With us also is John Plotz, who
is the professor of Victorian

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:39.190
literature at
Brandeis University,

00:03:39.190 --> 00:03:43.000
author of a new book
entitled Semi-Detached--

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.095
the Aesthetics of Virtual
Experience Since Dickens.

00:03:47.095 --> 00:03:50.530
He is also the author of
two other wonderful books--

00:03:50.530 --> 00:03:54.160
The Crowd-- British Literature
and Public Politics,

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:56.140
and Portable Property--

00:03:56.140 --> 00:03:58.550
Victorian Culture on the Move.

00:03:58.550 --> 00:04:03.580
And I understand he has also
written a young adult novel.

00:04:03.580 --> 00:04:05.470
Maybe we'll hear about that.

00:04:05.470 --> 00:04:09.050
Neither Marina nor John
is a stranger to Harvard.

00:04:09.050 --> 00:04:12.032
But I'd like to welcome
them back very warmly

00:04:12.032 --> 00:04:12.740
on this occasion.

00:04:17.420 --> 00:04:18.360
OK.

00:04:18.360 --> 00:04:20.099
Can you hear me?

00:04:20.099 --> 00:04:20.640
Yeah, really?

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:21.870
Because I can't hear myself.

00:04:21.870 --> 00:04:22.630
Oh, yeah, OK.

00:04:22.630 --> 00:04:23.470
Very good.

00:04:23.470 --> 00:04:25.680
Thank you so much for coming.

00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:28.450
It's unbelievable
that you're all here.

00:04:28.450 --> 00:04:32.310
I wouldn't get out of
bed with this cold,

00:04:32.310 --> 00:04:36.120
but I'm glad you did.

00:04:36.120 --> 00:04:38.820
First of all, I
want to thank Robin.

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:40.710
I want to thank Steve.

00:04:40.710 --> 00:04:44.310
I want to thank John also
for writing this book, which

00:04:44.310 --> 00:04:48.090
is, you know, when I was
asked, I thought, whoa,

00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:53.070
I wrote this tiny thing,
which I call my pamphlet.

00:04:53.070 --> 00:04:54.210
And he writes this.

00:04:54.210 --> 00:04:56.340
And I'm thinking, my
god, he's so lucky.

00:04:56.340 --> 00:04:57.270
He gets on later.

00:04:57.270 --> 00:05:00.600
But actually I love
every page of this book.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:03.720
So I really recommend it.

00:05:03.720 --> 00:05:08.590
And it reads a little bit like
a Victorian novel sometimes.

00:05:08.590 --> 00:05:09.090
All right.

00:05:09.090 --> 00:05:10.920
So let me begin.

00:05:10.920 --> 00:05:16.290
I'm going to just introduce
succinctly, I hope,

00:05:16.290 --> 00:05:18.390
what my book is about.

00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:22.830
So I decided to write this
book after I taught a class

00:05:22.830 --> 00:05:26.370
on promoting good idleness.

00:05:26.370 --> 00:05:28.680
And many of the
students in this class

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:31.650
confessed to me that
they were on Adderall,

00:05:31.650 --> 00:05:35.760
and they were on Ritalin, and
they let me on to the fact

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:41.220
that their pills made them feel
overly focused, helping them

00:05:41.220 --> 00:05:45.270
maybe get better results on
their papers, on their exams,

00:05:45.270 --> 00:05:47.970
but robbing them
of the pleasures

00:05:47.970 --> 00:05:53.110
and intellectual enrichment
of delayed gratification.

00:05:53.110 --> 00:05:56.160
They told me that they
missed the open time

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:59.460
that they thought
should be associated

00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:02.010
with novels and poetry.

00:06:02.010 --> 00:06:06.840
The class turned out to be an
unexpected exercise in soul

00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:11.490
searching about the connection
between success, media,

00:06:11.490 --> 00:06:15.870
technology, and the
lost art of slowness.

00:06:15.870 --> 00:06:19.950
It also reminded me,
while I was enrolling

00:06:19.950 --> 00:06:22.620
the students of this
class, it reminded me

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:25.920
of my first really hugely
traumatic experience,

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:29.730
which happened many, many,
many years ago at Harvard

00:06:29.730 --> 00:06:35.160
as a freshman when, after taking
some little test the first day,

00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:40.410
I was told that my reading
skills were particularly poor--

00:06:40.410 --> 00:06:43.470
how great for the
self-esteem right away--

00:06:43.470 --> 00:06:46.920
and that I would have to
enroll in Harvard's very

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:50.460
special speed-reading class.

00:06:50.460 --> 00:06:53.370
The first morning,
about a hundred of us,

00:06:53.370 --> 00:06:58.540
looking very sheepish-- and
none of us told our families--

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:00.840
so we sat in this
huge amphitheater.

00:07:00.840 --> 00:07:02.730
It was the Science Center.

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:07.760
And large chunks of text were
projected on a giant screen.

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:09.720
The instructions were clear.

00:07:09.720 --> 00:07:13.300
We needed to distill
what we read,

00:07:13.300 --> 00:07:15.780
and answer pointed
questions in order

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:19.560
to indicate that we had
grasped the argument.

00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:25.200
There was an obnoxious person
next to me, this woman speed

00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:29.340
reader who spoke so fast that I
couldn't imagine for one second

00:07:29.340 --> 00:07:31.530
that she needed to
take this class.

00:07:31.530 --> 00:07:34.170
And she looked at me,
and she said, oh, I

00:07:34.170 --> 00:07:37.170
understand that you're a
Russian literature major.

00:07:37.170 --> 00:07:40.290
Well, this class is going
to benefit you immensely,

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:43.530
because you will be able to
read The Brothers Karamazov

00:07:43.530 --> 00:07:47.490
in a fraction of the time.

00:07:47.490 --> 00:07:51.150
I was, needless
to say, horrified.

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:52.870
Who is this person?

00:07:52.870 --> 00:07:53.990
And she came from Belgium.

00:07:53.990 --> 00:07:56.940
And, I mean, I came from
France, so there was already

00:07:56.940 --> 00:07:58.470
this tension between us.

00:07:58.470 --> 00:08:00.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:04.290
So this horrible
experience was decades

00:08:04.290 --> 00:08:06.990
before the various
slow movements

00:08:06.990 --> 00:08:09.030
were encouraging
people to linger

00:08:09.030 --> 00:08:12.000
over their foods
and their futures.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.700
We had no computers
back then, remember?

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:18.330
And we would never have dreamt
of something I hope never

00:08:18.330 --> 00:08:22.870
have heard of, which is
Google's Popular Passages,

00:08:22.870 --> 00:08:27.300
a program that lets you
explore a book in 10 seconds,

00:08:27.300 --> 00:08:32.130
pointing out what really
is important when we read.

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:35.070
Naturally, no literature
lover could either

00:08:35.070 --> 00:08:37.559
have designed either
Google program,

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:41.190
or that atrocious speed-reading
class, which actually

00:08:41.190 --> 00:08:43.650
never helped me in the least.

00:08:43.650 --> 00:08:47.190
So Darwin, as you
will see, would

00:08:47.190 --> 00:08:50.040
have been the first
objector to this kind

00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:53.550
of traumatic
speed-reading experience.

00:08:53.550 --> 00:09:00.240
In this stunning entry from
his journal from May 1st, 1881,

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:06.000
he bitterly concludes
that extreme focus

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:12.790
can be dangerous-- in fact,
more dangerous than distraction.

00:09:12.790 --> 00:09:16.390
His extreme focus on
evolution, he writes,

00:09:16.390 --> 00:09:21.580
ended up shriveling his brain,
shutting out his favorite poets

00:09:21.580 --> 00:09:27.460
and musicians, and impairing
for good his judgment of taste.

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:30.040
I'm going to read
you a passage which

00:09:30.040 --> 00:09:33.275
is really heartbreaking
and beautiful from Darwin's

00:09:33.275 --> 00:09:33.775
journal.

00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:41.400
"Up to the age of 30 or beyond
it, poetry of many kinds

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:45.360
gave me great pleasure,
and even as a schoolboy

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:48.450
I took intense delight
in Shakespeare.

00:09:48.450 --> 00:09:53.430
I have also said that formerly
pictures gave me considerable--

00:09:53.430 --> 00:09:56.400
and music very great-- delight.

00:09:56.400 --> 00:09:59.610
I have tried lately
to read Shakespeare,

00:09:59.610 --> 00:10:06.030
and found it so intolerably
dull that it nauseated me.

00:10:06.030 --> 00:10:11.280
"I have also almost lost my
taste for pictures or music.

00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:13.930
My mind--" then pay
attention to this,

00:10:13.930 --> 00:10:15.810
because it's quite
heartbreaking--

00:10:15.810 --> 00:10:20.640
"My mind seems to have
become a kind of machine

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:27.750
for grinding general laws out
of large collections of fact.

00:10:27.750 --> 00:10:31.470
But why this should have
caused the atrophy of that part

00:10:31.470 --> 00:10:36.030
of the brain alone on which
the higher tastes depend,

00:10:36.030 --> 00:10:38.910
I cannot conceive.

00:10:38.910 --> 00:10:41.730
"If I had to live
my life again, I

00:10:41.730 --> 00:10:44.910
would have made a rule
to read some poetry

00:10:44.910 --> 00:10:48.960
and listen to some music
at least once a week."

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:49.830
Once a week.

00:10:49.830 --> 00:10:52.800
That is really
pitiful, Mr. Darwin.

00:10:52.800 --> 00:10:55.176
Once an hour.

00:10:55.176 --> 00:10:56.550
Well, he hated
leaving his house.

00:10:56.550 --> 00:10:57.180
He did.

00:10:57.180 --> 00:10:58.470
That's true.

00:10:58.470 --> 00:11:04.800
"The loss of these tastes," he
adds, "is a loss of happiness,

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:08.790
and may possibly be
injurious to the intellect,

00:11:08.790 --> 00:11:12.580
and more probably to
the moral character."

00:11:12.580 --> 00:11:16.740
So if losing one's train of
thought is such a bad thing,

00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:19.680
then why didn't
evolution fix it,

00:11:19.680 --> 00:11:24.240
providing us with a
steel-like concentration?

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:28.740
Could it be that destruction
grants us actually

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:32.940
a secret survivalist weapon?

00:11:32.940 --> 00:11:39.510
Unlike our primate siblings,
with their fierce capacity

00:11:39.510 --> 00:11:44.100
for fending off enemies,
finding food, securing shelter,

00:11:44.100 --> 00:11:48.150
we are programmed, for
better or for worse,

00:11:48.150 --> 00:11:51.750
for making light
of our condition.

00:11:51.750 --> 00:11:55.290
As the great anthropologist
Albert Piette--

00:11:55.290 --> 00:12:00.000
P-I-E-T-T-E; he should be
world famous, and he's not--

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.750
as Albert Piette notes,
as opposed to gorillas

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:06.810
and chimpanzee,
being human means

00:12:06.810 --> 00:12:11.640
to inhabit a presence
absence mode,

00:12:11.640 --> 00:12:14.760
to practice detached
attentiveness,

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:20.340
letting the minor and
major modes coexist.

00:12:20.340 --> 00:12:24.000
This minimalism, he
writes, allows us never

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:27.300
to get too deep
into things, dipping

00:12:27.300 --> 00:12:30.690
as we are in
activities peripheral

00:12:30.690 --> 00:12:33.390
to the situation at hand.

00:12:33.390 --> 00:12:37.590
So what can we learn from
the fact that only humans can

00:12:37.590 --> 00:12:41.550
be simultaneously
absent and present,

00:12:41.550 --> 00:12:43.930
detached and connected--

00:12:43.930 --> 00:12:47.920
thank you-- active and passive.

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:52.680
I think it is, because we
daydream, zone out, lose

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:56.490
our thread of a conversation,
that we can perhaps

00:12:56.490 --> 00:12:59.760
stop ourselves from
being fanatics,

00:12:59.760 --> 00:13:03.690
forget the harshest
blows, and move on.

00:13:03.690 --> 00:13:07.020
Many of you surely
remember a comment

00:13:07.020 --> 00:13:11.070
Primo Levi made in If This
is a Man, where he suggests

00:13:11.070 --> 00:13:16.170
that the paradoxical view
that divided attention might

00:13:16.170 --> 00:13:20.550
have done more good
than harm in Auschwitz.

00:13:20.550 --> 00:13:24.330
Despite his unthinkable
misery, Levi

00:13:24.330 --> 00:13:29.820
felt grateful that at least
on one fateful day the wind

00:13:29.820 --> 00:13:33.820
was not blowing too hard.

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:39.210
So what do we make of the
fact that only Homo sapiens

00:13:39.210 --> 00:13:43.560
is capable of the kind
of existential detachment

00:13:43.560 --> 00:13:48.150
that tolerates an idea that
goes nowhere, a thought that

00:13:48.150 --> 00:13:50.820
is never carried through?

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:52.920
The upside of this
is that we will

00:13:52.920 --> 00:13:56.210
endure, far better
than primates,

00:13:56.210 --> 00:14:01.620
a weirdly constructive
cognitive blurriness.

00:14:01.620 --> 00:14:05.640
So what if we can concentrate
on our work all the time?

00:14:05.640 --> 00:14:07.300
I know we're worried about that.

00:14:07.300 --> 00:14:09.990
We're worried every time
we look at our telephone.

00:14:09.990 --> 00:14:13.880
We're worried every time
we Google John Plotz.

00:14:13.880 --> 00:14:17.370
Oh, that's how I recognized
you-- because I googled you.

00:14:17.370 --> 00:14:21.600
So swaying between
crucial or less crucial

00:14:21.600 --> 00:14:27.120
occurrences may well constitute
strength, and not weakness--

00:14:27.120 --> 00:14:32.560
a very idiosyncratic type
of intellectual creativity,

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:36.240
one that feeds on
divided attention,

00:14:36.240 --> 00:14:41.820
and helps us balance the
playful and the tragic.

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:45.270
You all have read that
neurologists experimenting

00:14:45.270 --> 00:14:48.480
on ways people
solve problems note

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:51.810
that our best chance of
getting something right,

00:14:51.810 --> 00:14:56.350
getting a solution, is
to indulge in downtime.

00:14:56.350 --> 00:15:01.830
As you know, Nietzsche never had
an idea without perambulating.

00:15:01.830 --> 00:15:04.560
He needed to walk aimlessly.

00:15:04.560 --> 00:15:08.520
He needed to daydream
and to get lost in order

00:15:08.520 --> 00:15:10.740
to have that thought
that was somewhere

00:15:10.740 --> 00:15:13.110
in the back of its mind.

00:15:13.110 --> 00:15:15.900
Indeed, putting
the riddle at rest,

00:15:15.900 --> 00:15:18.840
and storing it at the
back of our minds,

00:15:18.840 --> 00:15:22.290
rather than focusing
on it ad nauseam

00:15:22.290 --> 00:15:26.580
liberates the
circuitry of thinking.

00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:32.400
Hume's wonderful formula,
the storehouse of labor,

00:15:32.400 --> 00:15:35.880
recalibrates perfectly
the dichotomy

00:15:35.880 --> 00:15:41.320
between work and play,
attention and inattention.

00:15:41.320 --> 00:15:45.300
Thinking in a straight line,
monitoring our every thought,

00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:50.040
is basically a losing battle
more and more, and we know it.

00:15:50.040 --> 00:15:52.980
Our innate way of relating
to our surroundings,

00:15:52.980 --> 00:15:57.180
and to our own thinking
patterns, is non-directed.

00:15:57.180 --> 00:16:02.670
Trapped by competing sensory
and intellectual stimuli

00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:07.560
we are, and it is,
essentially absent-minded.

00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:11.310
Tristram Shandy's meandering
account of his birth

00:16:11.310 --> 00:16:13.420
is a case in point.

00:16:13.420 --> 00:16:16.200
The more Sterne's
protagonist attempts

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:20.730
to control the intricacies
of his own autobiography,

00:16:20.730 --> 00:16:25.950
the more facts keep creeping in,
crowding his initial narrative,

00:16:25.950 --> 00:16:30.120
until it loses its
shape altogether.

00:16:30.120 --> 00:16:33.810
But let's go back to
David Hume for a moment--

00:16:33.810 --> 00:16:36.240
the wonderful David Hume.

00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:42.930
Hume cultivated an associative
random playful relationship

00:16:42.930 --> 00:16:47.340
to things as part of
a desire to stray away

00:16:47.340 --> 00:16:50.550
from this straight line,
and experience life

00:16:50.550 --> 00:16:56.820
as a series of rich,
disconnected moments.

00:16:56.820 --> 00:17:00.990
To begin with, Hume's
resistance to single-mindedness

00:17:00.990 --> 00:17:05.640
coincides with a
warm-blooded engagement

00:17:05.640 --> 00:17:07.510
with worldly matters.

00:17:07.510 --> 00:17:12.210
While concentration seems to him
solipsistic and self-involved,

00:17:12.210 --> 00:17:17.880
distraction, he muses provides
kinship and community.

00:17:17.880 --> 00:17:20.940
Let's think about that
when we're suicidally

00:17:20.940 --> 00:17:23.670
looking at our text messages.

00:17:23.670 --> 00:17:28.170
This is what he writes, and
it's one of my favorite quotes.

00:17:28.170 --> 00:17:31.620
"I dine-- he writes
that when he was just

00:17:31.620 --> 00:17:35.730
monomaniacally attempting
to disprove Descartes.

00:17:35.730 --> 00:17:37.800
And he just hated Descartes.

00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:39.489
But he got so
obsessed by Descartes

00:17:39.489 --> 00:17:41.280
that he thought, how
am I going to get away

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:44.160
from this French, crazy man?

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:46.650
I will play backgammon.

00:17:46.650 --> 00:17:49.470
I mean, maybe that's what we
should be doing right now.

00:17:49.470 --> 00:17:50.700
This is what he writes--

00:17:50.700 --> 00:17:53.940
"I dine, I play a
game of backgammon,

00:17:53.940 --> 00:17:57.180
I converse, I merry
with my friends.

00:17:57.180 --> 00:18:00.570
And when, after the three
or four hours of amusement,

00:18:00.570 --> 00:18:04.710
I would return to these
Cartesian speculations.

00:18:04.710 --> 00:18:09.450
They appear so cold, so
strained, ridiculous,

00:18:09.450 --> 00:18:14.640
that I cannot find in my heart
to enter into them any farther.

00:18:14.640 --> 00:18:18.240
I still feel such remains
of my former disposition

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:20.940
that I am ready to
throw all my books

00:18:20.940 --> 00:18:23.250
and papers into the fire"--

00:18:23.250 --> 00:18:25.470
please don't do that,
you graduate students

00:18:25.470 --> 00:18:27.690
with your dissertations--

00:18:27.690 --> 00:18:31.890
"and resolve never more to
renounce the pleasure of life

00:18:31.890 --> 00:18:35.400
for the sake of reasoning
and philosophy."

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:38.130
So, unlike many of us
beating ourselves up

00:18:38.130 --> 00:18:44.010
for neglecting reasoning, and
overindulging in play or text

00:18:44.010 --> 00:18:49.260
messages, Hume embraces
banter and backgammon

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:53.100
as therapies against
excessive focus.

00:18:53.100 --> 00:18:56.970
So, excessive focus is
worse than distraction.

00:18:56.970 --> 00:18:59.250
Take comfort in that.

00:18:59.250 --> 00:19:02.010
Excessive focus is the enemy.

00:19:02.010 --> 00:19:06.990
Playing devil's advocate to
Descartes's harsh critique

00:19:06.990 --> 00:19:11.610
of impure reasoning,
ridiculing the propensity

00:19:11.610 --> 00:19:16.030
to chase after
microcosmic dilemmas,

00:19:16.030 --> 00:19:20.700
if philosophy promotes such
claustrophobic thinking,

00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:25.290
then Hume would trade it
willfully and willingly

00:19:25.290 --> 00:19:27.960
for an open conversation.

00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:32.400
It may be mildly amusing to
you to know that this small

00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:33.840
pamphlet that I wrote--

00:19:33.840 --> 00:19:37.080
I like calling it a pamphlet,
because really, I mean,

00:19:37.080 --> 00:19:39.210
does this qualify as a book?

00:19:39.210 --> 00:19:40.130
I don't think so.

00:19:40.130 --> 00:19:41.220
It's like bullion.

00:19:41.220 --> 00:19:42.170
It's like what?

00:19:42.170 --> 00:19:42.910
Bullion.

00:19:42.910 --> 00:19:43.460
Oh, OK.

00:19:43.460 --> 00:19:44.700
All right.

00:19:44.700 --> 00:19:50.450
So this used to be 300
pages, and so boring.

00:19:50.450 --> 00:19:52.910
And I thought, really?

00:19:52.910 --> 00:19:56.360
Am I going to torture
my friends who

00:19:56.360 --> 00:20:02.450
are going to feel that they
have to read 300 pages of this?

00:20:02.450 --> 00:20:06.000
And you did not make me bored.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.760
So maybe I should have
kept it at 300 pages.

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:10.020
But I don't think so.

00:20:10.020 --> 00:20:13.680
But I decided to cut it down,
and to make it into something

00:20:13.680 --> 00:20:15.990
that people may be
able to read while they

00:20:15.990 --> 00:20:19.500
were sipping margarita.

00:20:19.500 --> 00:20:24.750
So one of the texts
that inspired me not

00:20:24.750 --> 00:20:29.730
to bore my audience
is a wonderful quote

00:20:29.730 --> 00:20:32.580
from Kierkegaard's Either/Or.

00:20:32.580 --> 00:20:34.680
This is Kierkegaard,
who is following

00:20:34.680 --> 00:20:38.100
the vagaries of his
own mind, who is trying

00:20:38.100 --> 00:20:41.070
to concentrate on a speaker.

00:20:41.070 --> 00:20:43.470
Just like you,
he's sitting there,

00:20:43.470 --> 00:20:48.030
and he thinks he's just going
to die, or to fall asleep.

00:20:48.030 --> 00:20:52.530
And suddenly he is
jolted out of his slumber

00:20:52.530 --> 00:20:56.430
by the least philosophical
part of the experience.

00:20:56.430 --> 00:21:01.800
He suddenly notices the
perspiration dripping down

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:06.000
this philosopher's
forehead and nose.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:07.770
I read to you.

00:21:07.770 --> 00:21:10.860
"There was a man
whose chatter I was

00:21:10.860 --> 00:21:15.390
obliged to listen to because
of the circumstances."

00:21:15.390 --> 00:21:17.850
God knows which circumstances.

00:21:17.850 --> 00:21:22.080
"On every occasion he was ready
with a little philosophical

00:21:22.080 --> 00:21:25.920
lecture that was
extremely boring.

00:21:25.920 --> 00:21:28.770
"On the verge of
despair, I suddenly

00:21:28.770 --> 00:21:33.720
discovered that the man
perspired exceptionally much

00:21:33.720 --> 00:21:35.520
when he spoke.

00:21:35.520 --> 00:21:39.660
This perspiration now
absorbed my attention.

00:21:39.660 --> 00:21:43.800
I watched how the pearls
of perspiration collected

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:51.840
on his forehead, then united in
a rivulet, slid down his nose,

00:21:51.840 --> 00:22:00.150
and ended in a quivering
globula that remained suspended

00:22:00.150 --> 00:22:02.820
at the end of his nose.

00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:06.630
From that moment on,
everything changed.

00:22:06.630 --> 00:22:10.710
I could even have the
delight of encourage

00:22:10.710 --> 00:22:13.950
him to commence his
philosophical instructions

00:22:13.950 --> 00:22:20.340
again, just in order to watch
the perspiration on his brow

00:22:20.340 --> 00:22:22.620
and on his nose."

00:22:22.620 --> 00:22:26.440
As he explains in the prologue
to this comical interlude,

00:22:26.440 --> 00:22:29.400
Kierkegaard can be
fantastically funny.

00:22:29.400 --> 00:22:32.580
The secret of
pleasurable attention

00:22:32.580 --> 00:22:37.170
is arbitrariness, often
the de-familiarized, even

00:22:37.170 --> 00:22:39.390
inappropriate kind.

00:22:39.390 --> 00:22:42.090
Carried by playfulness
and irreverence,

00:22:42.090 --> 00:22:46.540
Kierkegaard ended up
tolerating the trying

00:22:46.540 --> 00:22:51.550
boredom of the situation.

00:22:51.550 --> 00:22:54.940
What the wonderful
Albert Piette saw

00:22:54.940 --> 00:22:58.270
as our great hidden
strength, the ability

00:22:58.270 --> 00:23:05.010
to be simultaneously
present and absent, Mister--

00:23:05.010 --> 00:23:12.460
how could I call him;
brain-numbing and joy-killing--

00:23:12.460 --> 00:23:15.400
Heidegger sees as our doom.

00:23:15.400 --> 00:23:18.490
Believe me, I love
Heidegger too, sometimes,

00:23:18.490 --> 00:23:23.950
but boredom is something that to
him, as opposed to Kierkegaard,

00:23:23.950 --> 00:23:27.080
is absolutely necessary.

00:23:27.080 --> 00:23:31.000
So let's not focus on
someone's perspiration

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:32.650
when we read Heidegger.

00:23:32.650 --> 00:23:37.480
In fact, Heidegger wants us
chained to our attention,

00:23:37.480 --> 00:23:41.770
chained to our boredom,
advocating scrupulous

00:23:41.770 --> 00:23:42.880
attentiveness.

00:23:42.880 --> 00:23:46.240
He berates his readers
for drifting off,

00:23:46.240 --> 00:23:49.390
for going after
short-term satisfaction.

00:23:49.390 --> 00:23:55.930
Focus must be redirected to
the delicate textures of moods.

00:23:55.930 --> 00:23:58.720
"Without boredom,"
warns Heidegger,

00:23:58.720 --> 00:24:01.690
"we will go through
life like automata,

00:24:01.690 --> 00:24:04.870
not experiencing
anything in depth.

00:24:04.870 --> 00:24:08.740
Time would be mindlessly
allowed to fly by, and be

00:24:08.740 --> 00:24:10.330
frittered away.

00:24:10.330 --> 00:24:14.200
Only boredom, if fully
realized and grappled with,

00:24:14.200 --> 00:24:19.180
will keep us
existentially alert."

00:24:19.180 --> 00:24:22.080
We can debate this afterwards.

00:24:22.080 --> 00:24:26.430
I would like to finish, because
we only have a few minutes.

00:24:26.430 --> 00:24:28.860
I want to finish
with a marvelous

00:24:28.860 --> 00:24:32.550
quote that my wonderful
niece, who just finished

00:24:32.550 --> 00:24:36.180
her dissertation, and who
is doing a lot of googling,

00:24:36.180 --> 00:24:38.700
I think, in her free time.

00:24:38.700 --> 00:24:41.280
She wrote to me and
said, for your lecture

00:24:41.280 --> 00:24:43.360
you need to read this.

00:24:43.360 --> 00:24:47.710
And I have to confess, she
said, I got it off Wikipedia.

00:24:47.710 --> 00:24:53.370
So I am finishing this lecture
with a quote from Wikipedia.

00:24:53.370 --> 00:24:55.870
That's a pretty good
confession, right?

00:24:55.870 --> 00:24:58.680
How often do we tell our
students that this is directly

00:24:58.680 --> 00:25:00.340
from Wikipedia?

00:25:00.340 --> 00:25:04.530
So "Adam Smith,
writes Wikipedia,

00:25:04.530 --> 00:25:08.790
"was described by several of his
contemporaries and biographers

00:25:08.790 --> 00:25:13.890
as comically absent-minded,
with peculiar habits of speech

00:25:13.890 --> 00:25:20.400
and gait, and a smile of
inexpressible benignity.

00:25:20.400 --> 00:25:23.400
He was known to talk to
himself, a habit, that

00:25:23.400 --> 00:25:26.010
began during his
childhood, and he

00:25:26.010 --> 00:25:33.000
would smile in rapt conversation
with invisible companions.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:36.810
"According to one story,
Smith took one of his friends

00:25:36.810 --> 00:25:40.590
on a tour of a tanning
factory, and while discussing

00:25:40.590 --> 00:25:46.410
free trade, he walked into a
huge tanning pit, from which he

00:25:46.410 --> 00:25:50.100
needed help to escape.

00:25:50.100 --> 00:25:53.280
He is also said to have
put bread and butter

00:25:53.280 --> 00:25:57.300
into a teapot, drunk
the concoction,

00:25:57.300 --> 00:26:03.390
and declared this is the worst
cup of tea I have ever had.

00:26:03.390 --> 00:26:06.930
According to another
account, Smith distractedly

00:26:06.930 --> 00:26:09.420
went out walking
in his nightgown,

00:26:09.420 --> 00:26:12.770
and ended up 15
miles outside of town

00:26:12.770 --> 00:26:17.770
before nearby church bells
brought him back to reality."

00:26:17.770 --> 00:26:20.640
So I just want to thank
you for being here.

00:26:20.640 --> 00:26:22.740
And if you don't
buy this book, do

00:26:22.740 --> 00:26:26.560
try to get it on
Google's Popular Passage.

00:26:26.560 --> 00:26:30.000
Remember, it's a program that
will let you understand it

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:31.470
in 10 seconds.

00:26:31.470 --> 00:26:32.637
Thank you.

00:26:32.637 --> 00:26:36.930
[APPLAUSE]

00:26:38.741 --> 00:26:39.240
Sorry.

00:26:39.240 --> 00:26:42.370
So I'm going to hide behind
a PowerPoint a little bit.

00:26:42.370 --> 00:26:46.410
So, thank you so much,
Robin, for this event.

00:26:46.410 --> 00:26:49.720
And thanks to Sarah and to
Steve for organizing it.

00:26:49.720 --> 00:26:51.750
And Marina, thank you so much.

00:26:51.750 --> 00:26:52.810
It's great.

00:26:52.810 --> 00:26:55.950
I threatened that I was going
to read the Kierkegaard passage

00:26:55.950 --> 00:26:57.330
from Marina's book
if she didn't.

00:26:57.330 --> 00:27:00.000
So it's like a Good Place
episode, or something.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:02.500
It's fantastic.

00:27:02.500 --> 00:27:05.306
So it is a really great
pleasure to be here tonight,

00:27:05.306 --> 00:27:06.930
and to take part in
what I look forward

00:27:06.930 --> 00:27:10.110
to being just an open
conversation, and freewheeling.

00:27:10.110 --> 00:27:12.840
But like Marina, I'm going
to just talk a little bit

00:27:12.840 --> 00:27:14.700
to set things up.

00:27:14.700 --> 00:27:17.310
So the way I would frame
it is that nowadays we

00:27:17.310 --> 00:27:21.630
have diagnoses
like ADD, or ADHD,

00:27:21.630 --> 00:27:24.960
and we have the account
of social media addiction,

00:27:24.960 --> 00:27:29.820
or Google-itis, to anchor our
discussion of distraction.

00:27:29.820 --> 00:27:32.880
And so maybe we could think
about that amazing eyeball

00:27:32.880 --> 00:27:34.570
as the figure for that.

00:27:34.570 --> 00:27:36.330
Though I have to
admit to me it has

00:27:36.330 --> 00:27:39.240
kind of a Nordic Sauron vibe.

00:27:39.240 --> 00:27:42.190
It seems more hypervigilant
than distracted.

00:27:42.190 --> 00:27:46.350
But, you know, I
get it's the problem

00:27:46.350 --> 00:27:48.540
of the skipping
eyeball, I guess.

00:27:48.540 --> 00:27:51.160
So we have that now in spades.

00:27:51.160 --> 00:27:53.920
But I mean, even when
I was growing up,

00:27:53.920 --> 00:27:57.120
there were ways of
thinking about distraction

00:27:57.120 --> 00:27:58.410
as a common problem.

00:27:58.410 --> 00:28:04.080
So I remember as a kid the Monty
Python sketch "Word Association

00:28:04.080 --> 00:28:04.659
Football."

00:28:04.659 --> 00:28:06.450
I don't know how many
people remember this.

00:28:06.450 --> 00:28:09.300
But it's John Cleese telling
you-- it's very hard to do.

00:28:09.300 --> 00:28:11.160
I mean, I've never said
it out loud before,

00:28:11.160 --> 00:28:12.360
but I got the words.

00:28:12.360 --> 00:28:17.120
It's "Word association
football is a technique out

00:28:17.120 --> 00:28:21.260
a living much used in the
practice makes perfect

00:28:21.260 --> 00:28:24.630
of psychoanalysister
and brother,

00:28:24.630 --> 00:28:29.190
and one that has occupied
piper the majority rule

00:28:29.190 --> 00:28:32.520
of my attention squad by the
right number one, two, three,

00:28:32.520 --> 00:28:34.920
four, the last five years."

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:36.300
So you get the idea.

00:28:36.300 --> 00:28:39.900
There, each word, or
even each syllable,

00:28:39.900 --> 00:28:44.100
is kicking the distracted
brain or the distracted tongue

00:28:44.100 --> 00:28:48.030
away down a fresh pathway
to some kind of fresh hell.

00:28:48.030 --> 00:28:52.350
So it's kind of like
language itself as clickbait,

00:28:52.350 --> 00:28:56.340
that we're always capable of
being kicked sideways, even

00:28:56.340 --> 00:28:59.160
in "technique out a living."

00:28:59.160 --> 00:29:02.940
So in other words, there's
a very robust tradition

00:29:02.940 --> 00:29:05.220
of understanding
distraction as kind

00:29:05.220 --> 00:29:07.890
of free-range
mental peregrination

00:29:07.890 --> 00:29:10.800
with, as Marina was
saying, with all its vices.

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:13.110
So yes, new, Robin,
I totally agree.

00:29:13.110 --> 00:29:14.160
It is new.

00:29:14.160 --> 00:29:15.600
We have a new version of it.

00:29:15.600 --> 00:29:17.580
But then we also want
to think about how

00:29:17.580 --> 00:29:23.220
much the new version of it is
akin to older versions of it.

00:29:23.220 --> 00:29:28.020
So those are recent diagnoses
that medicalize or burlesque

00:29:28.020 --> 00:29:28.590
the state.

00:29:28.590 --> 00:29:31.170
But in the early
days of the church,

00:29:31.170 --> 00:29:36.090
the desert fathers were
obsessed with acedia,

00:29:36.090 --> 00:29:39.450
which sort of turns into
sloth or [? decedia ?]

00:29:39.450 --> 00:29:43.650
in later ages as a deadly
sin, but originally is

00:29:43.650 --> 00:29:46.170
the state of restlessness
and inability

00:29:46.170 --> 00:29:47.850
either to work or to pray.

00:29:47.850 --> 00:29:50.310
So that's the
original noonday demon

00:29:50.310 --> 00:29:54.150
is the demon that distracts you.

00:29:54.150 --> 00:29:59.910
And later on here, in the
shadow of William James Hall,

00:29:59.910 --> 00:30:03.690
it seems appropriate to recall
a line from his 1890 Principles

00:30:03.690 --> 00:30:05.880
of Psychology, which
actually I have

00:30:05.880 --> 00:30:08.280
to admit that I got not from
Wikipedia, but from Joshua

00:30:08.280 --> 00:30:11.460
Cohen's new book,
called Attention.

00:30:11.460 --> 00:30:13.380
But maybe he got
it from Wikipedia.

00:30:13.380 --> 00:30:14.760
It's totally possible.

00:30:14.760 --> 00:30:16.740
"Attention is the
taking possession

00:30:16.740 --> 00:30:19.920
of the mind in
clear and vivid form

00:30:19.920 --> 00:30:24.120
of one out of what seems several
simultaneously possible objects

00:30:24.120 --> 00:30:25.560
or trains of thought.

00:30:25.560 --> 00:30:29.820
It implies withdrawal from
some things in order to deal

00:30:29.820 --> 00:30:33.210
effectively with others, and
is a condition which has a real

00:30:33.210 --> 00:30:38.670
opposite in the confused,
dazed, scatterbrained state,

00:30:38.670 --> 00:30:41.660
which in French is called--" and
I will just say it in English

00:30:41.660 --> 00:30:43.500
"--distraction."

00:30:43.500 --> 00:30:48.690
However, so there is
this account of attention

00:30:48.690 --> 00:30:50.070
good, distraction bad.

00:30:50.070 --> 00:30:54.060
And clearly both of us here
are standing in front of you

00:30:54.060 --> 00:30:55.770
to discuss ways--

00:30:55.770 --> 00:30:58.420
other ways, maybe-- to
think about distraction,

00:30:58.420 --> 00:31:01.080
and I think not
necessarily to praise it.

00:31:01.080 --> 00:31:04.470
I really don't want my teenagers
to see on Twitter that I'm

00:31:04.470 --> 00:31:06.510
in favor of distraction.

00:31:06.510 --> 00:31:08.770
But at least not to bury it.

00:31:08.770 --> 00:31:12.450
So I thought the best
way to kick this off

00:31:12.450 --> 00:31:16.410
is to take about 15
or maybe 20 minutes

00:31:16.410 --> 00:31:20.100
to present the argument
of my book Semi-Detached.

00:31:20.100 --> 00:31:24.480
And Marina, in terms of the
amazing lapidary concision

00:31:24.480 --> 00:31:27.110
of your book, I feel
like about my book

00:31:27.110 --> 00:31:29.197
that there's I think
it's a Samuel Johnson

00:31:29.197 --> 00:31:31.530
line, I wrote a long letter,
because I did not have time

00:31:31.530 --> 00:31:32.490
to write a short one.

00:31:32.490 --> 00:31:34.770
So I think you went ahead
and wrote the short one.

00:31:34.770 --> 00:31:38.040
But I kind of
wrote the long one.

00:31:38.040 --> 00:31:43.397
And it is about this
idea of semi-detachment.

00:31:43.397 --> 00:31:45.480
So I'm just going to talk
a little bit about that.

00:31:45.480 --> 00:31:48.300
When you half lose
yourself in a work of art,

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:51.330
what happens to the half
that is left behind?

00:31:51.330 --> 00:31:54.570
The critical vocabulary
to describe that sensation

00:31:54.570 --> 00:31:58.200
is lacking, but it's a
familiar feeling nonetheless.

00:31:58.200 --> 00:32:00.630
When most carried
away, audiences

00:32:00.630 --> 00:32:02.550
of even the most
compelling artwork

00:32:02.550 --> 00:32:06.570
remain somewhat aware of
their actual situation.

00:32:06.570 --> 00:32:11.200
Ideas about this kind of
semi-detachment play a crucial,

00:32:11.200 --> 00:32:13.830
and I think an
under-explored role,

00:32:13.830 --> 00:32:17.100
in shaping a wide range
of modern artwork.

00:32:17.100 --> 00:32:20.220
So the argument of
the book is, yes, this

00:32:20.220 --> 00:32:23.300
is a kind of phenomenological
account of this feeling.

00:32:23.300 --> 00:32:25.470
But what I want to
show is that there's

00:32:25.470 --> 00:32:28.470
a lot of artworks
where the artist must

00:32:28.470 --> 00:32:29.460
be thinking about this.

00:32:29.460 --> 00:32:31.710
I mean, this is an
intentionalist account.

00:32:31.710 --> 00:32:35.220
So Marina, you very
rightly pointed

00:32:35.220 --> 00:32:39.000
to a key attribute of how we
think about distraction, which

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:41.040
is that the reader
should be free to pick up

00:32:41.040 --> 00:32:42.410
what they want to pick.

00:32:42.410 --> 00:32:44.160
That's the kind of
Roland Barthes account,

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:46.830
and pleasures of the
text, that the text

00:32:46.830 --> 00:32:49.110
may be there because
the author put it there.

00:32:49.110 --> 00:32:53.100
But either reader can take
up or put down what I want.

00:32:53.100 --> 00:32:56.040
And I agree with that as an
important way of thinking

00:32:56.040 --> 00:32:59.880
about what the conscious state
in front of a work of art

00:32:59.880 --> 00:33:02.380
is, as it is in
front of the world.

00:33:02.380 --> 00:33:05.670
But my argument is that the
artworks I want to talk about

00:33:05.670 --> 00:33:09.210
are ones where in the
inception of the artwork

00:33:09.210 --> 00:33:11.910
you already see that the
person making the art

00:33:11.910 --> 00:33:15.220
must have understood that kind
of doubleness as part of it.

00:33:15.220 --> 00:33:17.974
That isn't just a
readerly response

00:33:17.974 --> 00:33:19.890
that could be arbitrary,
it could be anything,

00:33:19.890 --> 00:33:23.250
but it's also a response to
something that's really--

00:33:23.250 --> 00:33:25.650
you can show it to be
present in the contours

00:33:25.650 --> 00:33:27.210
of the artwork itself.

00:33:27.210 --> 00:33:29.647
So I'm saying that
this is modern.

00:33:29.647 --> 00:33:31.980
And for me, it's really the
last couple of hundred years

00:33:31.980 --> 00:33:33.190
that I'm interested in.

00:33:33.190 --> 00:33:35.530
But it is definitely
there earlier.

00:33:35.530 --> 00:33:39.964
So in this 1595 amazing
painting by Caravaggio,

00:33:39.964 --> 00:33:41.880
for instance, which I
was sort of lucky enough

00:33:41.880 --> 00:33:47.677
to see in Canada early
days of this project, what

00:33:47.677 --> 00:33:49.260
I'm going to say--
and I think I'm not

00:33:49.260 --> 00:33:50.926
going to talk a ton
about this painting,

00:33:50.926 --> 00:33:53.634
but I'll come back to it.

00:33:53.634 --> 00:33:55.050
It's called The
Musicians, but I'm

00:33:55.050 --> 00:33:57.000
interested in the
central musician.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:59.670
So his hand on the
strings, the music

00:33:59.670 --> 00:34:01.620
that we can imagine
going through the air,

00:34:01.620 --> 00:34:05.677
his gaze out at us, which is
the gaze of kind of attention

00:34:05.677 --> 00:34:08.010
and inattention at once,
because, of course, he's tuning

00:34:08.010 --> 00:34:11.110
and he's listening, but
he's also looking out at us.

00:34:11.110 --> 00:34:14.580
But he's also not looking out
at us, because he's just canvas.

00:34:14.580 --> 00:34:17.400
He's just color on canvas,
so he's not really looking.

00:34:17.400 --> 00:34:19.386
But we kind of want
to catch his eye.

00:34:19.386 --> 00:34:20.760
But even if we
caught his eye, we

00:34:20.760 --> 00:34:23.854
wouldn't really catch him
looking at us, because he's

00:34:23.854 --> 00:34:25.020
listening to his instrument.

00:34:25.020 --> 00:34:27.810
So this play, this kind
of back and forth where

00:34:27.810 --> 00:34:31.830
we want to be drawn in, there's
a kind of claim of absorption.

00:34:31.830 --> 00:34:34.320
But then there's also
the reminder-- but wait,

00:34:34.320 --> 00:34:35.960
it's more complicated than that.

00:34:35.960 --> 00:34:40.030
You're outside looking
in at the same time.

00:34:40.030 --> 00:34:42.150
So in such words,
in works like this,

00:34:42.150 --> 00:34:44.460
the crux of an
aesthetic experience

00:34:44.460 --> 00:34:47.489
is imagined, or
depicted, or understood

00:34:47.489 --> 00:34:51.300
as residing neither in complete
absorption in an artwork,

00:34:51.300 --> 00:34:53.920
nor in critical
detachment from it,

00:34:53.920 --> 00:34:58.600
but in the odd fact of both
states existing simultaneously.

00:34:58.600 --> 00:35:01.407
So I'm not an art historian.

00:35:01.407 --> 00:35:03.240
I was going to say I'm
a fake art historian,

00:35:03.240 --> 00:35:04.823
but I'm not even a
fake art historian.

00:35:04.823 --> 00:35:06.330
Not an art historian.

00:35:06.330 --> 00:35:08.512
But so let me just talk
about just a couple

00:35:08.512 --> 00:35:10.720
of literary passages that
I want to talk about today.

00:35:10.720 --> 00:35:14.820
And so this is probably the
most important one for me.

00:35:14.820 --> 00:35:17.490
In George Eliot's The
Mill on the Floss,

00:35:17.490 --> 00:35:20.490
in the first chapter
moves from an account

00:35:20.490 --> 00:35:21.480
of the young heroine--

00:35:21.480 --> 00:35:24.630
Maggie Tulliver, you
may remember-- at play

00:35:24.630 --> 00:35:29.610
to a description of the benumbed
arms of the narrator who

00:35:29.610 --> 00:35:31.870
has been watching her.

00:35:31.870 --> 00:35:33.370
"It is time the
little playfellow--"

00:35:33.370 --> 00:35:34.960
so the narrator is
speaking to us--

00:35:34.960 --> 00:35:36.940
"It is time the little
playfellow went in,

00:35:36.940 --> 00:35:40.060
I think; and there's a very
bright fire to tempt her;

00:35:40.060 --> 00:35:42.520
the red light shines out
from under the deepening

00:35:42.520 --> 00:35:43.690
gray of the sky.

00:35:43.690 --> 00:35:45.880
It is time, too,
for me to leave off

00:35:45.880 --> 00:35:50.020
resting my arms on the
cold stone of this bridge."

00:35:50.020 --> 00:35:52.700
Ellipsis-- Eliot's
ellipsis, not mine.

00:35:52.700 --> 00:35:54.930
"Ah, my arms are
really benumbed.

00:35:54.930 --> 00:35:57.310
And I have been pressing
my elbows on the arms

00:35:57.310 --> 00:36:00.790
of my chair--" like this kind
of chair "--and dreaming that I

00:36:00.790 --> 00:36:03.520
was standing on the bridge in
front of Dorlcote Mill as it

00:36:03.520 --> 00:36:07.330
looked one February
afternoon many years ago."

00:36:07.330 --> 00:36:12.430
So Elliot has an image of
a doubled elbow rest here,

00:36:12.430 --> 00:36:15.120
the bridge and the
chair arm both.

00:36:15.120 --> 00:36:17.290
And I think that
offers a way to think

00:36:17.290 --> 00:36:19.420
about the reading
of the novel itself.

00:36:19.420 --> 00:36:25.270
Not only am I here reading,
I'm also there absorbed

00:36:25.270 --> 00:36:26.890
into their world.

00:36:26.890 --> 00:36:28.930
The narrator turns
into a simulacrum

00:36:28.930 --> 00:36:31.810
of the reader, whose dreamlike
entry into Maggie's world

00:36:31.810 --> 00:36:35.590
is bodied forth in that
ellipsis-marked discovery

00:36:35.590 --> 00:36:38.860
that the arms had been pressing
onto the bridge and the arm

00:36:38.860 --> 00:36:40.660
chair simultaneously.

00:36:40.660 --> 00:36:43.330
So one April morning,
not very far from here,

00:36:43.330 --> 00:36:46.210
biking over the Mass Pike,
listening to my iPod,

00:36:46.210 --> 00:36:49.780
back when there were iPods,
with traffic noise in one ear,

00:36:49.780 --> 00:36:52.120
and the Carter
family in the other,

00:36:52.120 --> 00:36:56.110
I suddenly came to think
about that moment in James

00:36:56.110 --> 00:37:00.640
as a fact of life,
not just of art.

00:37:00.640 --> 00:37:02.440
Holding two things
in my head at once--

00:37:02.440 --> 00:37:05.290
cabin in the pines, and
also the broken glass

00:37:05.290 --> 00:37:07.750
that I'd have to dodge at
the end of the footbridge,

00:37:07.750 --> 00:37:11.390
suddenly struck me less as
a quirk of George Eliot's

00:37:11.390 --> 00:37:15.460
armchair doubling, or,
yeah, elbow doubling,

00:37:15.460 --> 00:37:17.230
and more as a record
of something that

00:37:17.230 --> 00:37:20.890
had been happening to me
all my life, only happening

00:37:20.890 --> 00:37:24.460
in this evanescent and
unsatisfactory way,

00:37:24.460 --> 00:37:26.860
happening and then vanishing
again because I lacked

00:37:26.860 --> 00:37:28.690
the vocabulary to
make sense of it,

00:37:28.690 --> 00:37:31.630
to give it a name
and some attributes,

00:37:31.630 --> 00:37:35.110
and in that kind of scholarly
way, to try to historicize it.

00:37:35.110 --> 00:37:38.260
So the title of Sherry
Turkle's Jeremiah,

00:37:38.260 --> 00:37:40.510
wonderful Jeremiah,
but Jeremiah,

00:37:40.510 --> 00:37:44.260
about teenagers' over-networked
lives Alone Together,

00:37:44.260 --> 00:37:46.210
began to strike me
less as an indictment

00:37:46.210 --> 00:37:49.420
of our present social
condition than as a description

00:37:49.420 --> 00:37:51.430
of our perennial
residence in a state

00:37:51.430 --> 00:37:54.200
of mental quasi-abstraction.

00:37:54.200 --> 00:37:57.430
So I biked straight off that
bridge, and into the library--

00:37:57.430 --> 00:37:59.060
in fact, Widener Library.

00:37:59.060 --> 00:38:03.130
And sometimes it seems
that I have not left since.

00:38:03.130 --> 00:38:06.370
So just because it
took me until the 2010s

00:38:06.370 --> 00:38:09.657
to have this realization
did not mean, of course,

00:38:09.657 --> 00:38:11.740
that other people hadn't
been having it before me.

00:38:11.740 --> 00:38:13.531
And one of the joys
for me of Marina's book

00:38:13.531 --> 00:38:15.550
is to think about the
two of us discovering

00:38:15.550 --> 00:38:17.620
different genealogies
of this way

00:38:17.620 --> 00:38:21.760
that this is a thing that is
new now, and yet also keeps

00:38:21.760 --> 00:38:24.700
on happening in earlier times.

00:38:24.700 --> 00:38:28.150
So just to read you a Ford
Maddox Ford quote, "It is,

00:38:28.150 --> 00:38:31.240
I mean, perfectly possible
for a sensitized person,

00:38:31.240 --> 00:38:34.450
be he poet or prose writer,
to have the sense, when

00:38:34.450 --> 00:38:37.019
he's in one room,
that he is in another,

00:38:37.019 --> 00:38:38.560
or when he is speaking
to one person,

00:38:38.560 --> 00:38:42.790
he may be so haunted
by the memory or desire

00:38:42.790 --> 00:38:46.840
for another person that he may
be absent-minded or distraught.

00:38:46.840 --> 00:38:48.760
Indeed, I suppose
that impressionism

00:38:48.760 --> 00:38:52.600
exists to render those
queer effects of real life

00:38:52.600 --> 00:38:56.630
that are, like so many views,
seen through bright glass."

00:38:56.630 --> 00:39:00.460
So this is the double
image that he's setting up.

00:39:00.460 --> 00:39:03.760
"--seen through glass so
bright that whilst you perceive

00:39:03.760 --> 00:39:07.540
through it a landscape or
backyard, you are aware that,

00:39:07.540 --> 00:39:10.620
on its surface, it reflects a
face of a person behind you."

00:39:10.620 --> 00:39:11.620
So do you guys get that?

00:39:11.620 --> 00:39:12.430
It's like lens.

00:39:12.430 --> 00:39:16.210
It's pass-through and
lens, or mirror slash lens,

00:39:16.210 --> 00:39:18.730
and also pass-through
at the same time.

00:39:18.730 --> 00:39:21.130
"For the whole of life
is really like that.

00:39:21.130 --> 00:39:24.160
We are almost always in
one place with our minds

00:39:24.160 --> 00:39:27.880
somewhere quite another."

00:39:27.880 --> 00:39:31.750
And here, not just under
the shadow of William James,

00:39:31.750 --> 00:39:34.360
but also footsteps away
from 20 Quincy Street,

00:39:34.360 --> 00:39:37.420
where William and Henry lived--
it was before the Harvard

00:39:37.420 --> 00:39:41.350
Faculty Club was built on the
ruins of Henry's bedroom--

00:39:41.350 --> 00:39:45.880
we might also give some
thought to Henry James.

00:39:45.880 --> 00:39:48.820
Here he is describing the
protagonist of the tragic muse.

00:39:52.060 --> 00:39:57.100
And he picks up distraction,
and twisted a different way

00:39:57.100 --> 00:39:58.030
from William.

00:39:58.030 --> 00:40:00.760
So you remember William
talked about the-- let me get

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:01.480
the exact words--

00:40:01.480 --> 00:40:06.040
William talked about
the "confused, dazed

00:40:06.040 --> 00:40:07.330
scatterbrained state."

00:40:07.330 --> 00:40:11.440
But what Henry says is, at this
moment when he has sort of met

00:40:11.440 --> 00:40:15.010
this fetching new person he's
become interested in, "There

00:40:15.010 --> 00:40:17.440
was a new infusion in
his consciousness--

00:40:17.440 --> 00:40:20.410
an element in his life,
which altered the relations

00:40:20.410 --> 00:40:24.850
of things--" a new "distraction"
in the French sense "--he could

00:40:24.850 --> 00:40:29.170
recognize that as freely as
possible without being obliged

00:40:29.170 --> 00:40:32.300
to classify the agreeable
resources as a new

00:40:32.300 --> 00:40:33.420
entanglement."

00:40:33.420 --> 00:40:35.600
So I take it there
that an entitlement

00:40:35.600 --> 00:40:37.580
would be kind of like
what William James was

00:40:37.580 --> 00:40:39.380
talking about with attention.

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:42.380
An entitlement would kind of
anchor you to that person.

00:40:42.380 --> 00:40:45.440
But this is the
agreeable possibility

00:40:45.440 --> 00:40:48.050
of it being is a free relation.

00:40:48.050 --> 00:40:50.900
This infusion is kind
of a free infusion.

00:40:50.900 --> 00:40:53.540
And by the way, since
both the James brothers

00:40:53.540 --> 00:40:54.980
talk about this
as being French, I

00:40:54.980 --> 00:40:57.021
was like, OK, well, I'm
going to look at the OED.

00:40:57.021 --> 00:41:00.230
And in fact, if you
go to 1526, hard it

00:41:00.230 --> 00:41:03.650
is to say one paternoster
without distraction of mind.

00:41:03.650 --> 00:41:06.020
So in fact it's a
perfectly English--

00:41:06.020 --> 00:41:07.879
I mean, it is a
long-term English phrase,

00:41:07.879 --> 00:41:09.920
that the fact that people
think of it as French--

00:41:09.920 --> 00:41:10.795
I don't know, Marina.

00:41:10.795 --> 00:41:12.620
Maybe you have something
to say about that.

00:41:12.620 --> 00:41:16.250
They don't call it
Belgian, that's for sure.

00:41:16.250 --> 00:41:17.000
Yeah.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:19.160
But yeah.

00:41:19.160 --> 00:41:22.340
And that 16th
century usage of it,

00:41:22.340 --> 00:41:25.530
you can see there that's a
sort of an acedia problem,

00:41:25.530 --> 00:41:28.760
like when I pray, I find
my mind slipping away.

00:41:28.760 --> 00:41:32.200
So that's really a
classic distraction.

00:41:32.200 --> 00:41:33.080
OK.

00:41:33.080 --> 00:41:39.440
So we both came to this question
of how do we think about this.

00:41:39.440 --> 00:41:43.790
And I think for both of us,
what I wanted to emphasize--

00:41:43.790 --> 00:41:46.050
and I'm not going to talk
a lot about the next slide.

00:41:46.050 --> 00:41:51.260
But there is a way to say we
live in this world of beeping,

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:53.234
and buzzing, and
tweeting, and chirping.

00:41:53.234 --> 00:41:55.400
I don't know if anyone's
seen the new Wreck-It Ralph

00:41:55.400 --> 00:41:57.625
movie, about Ralph
entering the internet.

00:42:01.129 --> 00:42:01.670
I don't know.

00:42:01.670 --> 00:42:04.400
I had not been able to imagine
how many different forms

00:42:04.400 --> 00:42:06.560
of social mediation
you could discover kind

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:09.020
of swarming in on you at once.

00:42:09.020 --> 00:42:11.760
And Ralph sort of
experiences them all at once.

00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:13.340
And so you could
see the alternative,

00:42:13.340 --> 00:42:16.490
like Patrick Leigh Fermor's
wonderful book about going

00:42:16.490 --> 00:42:20.150
to a monastery, or this
interesting book by Kathleen

00:42:20.150 --> 00:42:22.130
Norris called
Acedia and Me, where

00:42:22.130 --> 00:42:24.920
she talks about taking
on the burdens of time

00:42:24.920 --> 00:42:26.127
by going to the desert.

00:42:26.127 --> 00:42:27.710
There's this Georgia
O'Keeffe painting

00:42:27.710 --> 00:42:32.960
I love to look at that has
that kind of desert serenity.

00:42:32.960 --> 00:42:35.660
But that's not the story,
I think, that either of us

00:42:35.660 --> 00:42:38.480
wants to tell about
what the alternative is

00:42:38.480 --> 00:42:43.780
to thinking about distraction
as just pure noise and babble.

00:42:43.780 --> 00:42:46.700
Instead, we really are
thinking about things

00:42:46.700 --> 00:42:49.940
like this Caravaggio
painting, this notion

00:42:49.940 --> 00:42:57.410
of the music that is there,
and is somehow kind of torquing

00:42:57.410 --> 00:43:01.310
that relationship we have to
the central musician figure.

00:43:01.310 --> 00:43:02.990
Maybe it's somewhat
different with a guy

00:43:02.990 --> 00:43:04.970
looking out over his
shoulder with a sort

00:43:04.970 --> 00:43:08.510
of more what I think of as a
Caravaggioesque come-hither

00:43:08.510 --> 00:43:09.710
look.

00:43:09.710 --> 00:43:12.440
But the difference
between those two faces

00:43:12.440 --> 00:43:16.700
may be giving us some sense of
different ways of looking out

00:43:16.700 --> 00:43:19.910
of a painting at
you calling you in.

00:43:19.910 --> 00:43:22.070
And then I talk a little
bit-- though, again,

00:43:22.070 --> 00:43:24.260
I feel very out of my
comfort zone here--

00:43:24.260 --> 00:43:27.340
about this amazing poem which
I just covered at the MFA,

00:43:27.340 --> 00:43:29.540
but painting-- interesting--

00:43:29.540 --> 00:43:32.150
Hans Memling, Christ
Blessing, in which

00:43:32.150 --> 00:43:35.270
really what I care
about here, which is not

00:43:35.270 --> 00:43:38.060
easy to see on the reproduction,
but the way that the hand just

00:43:38.060 --> 00:43:42.140
rests on this
seeming frame, which

00:43:42.140 --> 00:43:44.210
is a little bit of
a trompe l'oeil,

00:43:44.210 --> 00:43:45.826
but it isn't really
a trompe l'oeil

00:43:45.826 --> 00:43:47.450
that has meant to
have a gotcha effect.

00:43:47.450 --> 00:43:49.430
It's meant to more
just establish

00:43:49.430 --> 00:43:53.930
that the Christ is with
and not with you, that he's

00:43:53.930 --> 00:43:57.740
out there in that space, but
also somewhat potentially

00:43:57.740 --> 00:44:01.070
present in your own space.

00:44:01.070 --> 00:44:06.890
And I do feel a little
bit more comfortable

