00:44:31.610 --> 00:44:34.610
with Keaton sort
of in the 1920s,

00:44:34.610 --> 00:44:37.940
I just love how Buster Keaton
is able to think about what

00:44:37.940 --> 00:44:40.884
it means to kind of be
wrapped in your own world,

00:44:40.884 --> 00:44:42.425
and then suddenly
discover that there

00:44:42.425 --> 00:44:44.300
is a real world that intrudes.

00:44:44.300 --> 00:44:47.264
So we could talk a lot about the
comedy of Buster Keaton which

00:44:47.264 --> 00:44:48.680
unfolds in a lot
of different ways

00:44:48.680 --> 00:44:52.280
in terms of his investment,
and kind of mechanical comedy.

00:44:52.280 --> 00:44:55.970
But the emphasis for me, like in
the context of semi-detachment,

00:44:55.970 --> 00:44:59.630
the character, Buster, is
always moving through the world

00:44:59.630 --> 00:45:04.790
alone, and then just coming to
realize things about that world

00:45:04.790 --> 00:45:06.030
that he had not grasped.

00:45:06.030 --> 00:45:08.810
It's almost like he's got kind
of a transcendentalist problem,

00:45:08.810 --> 00:45:11.960
like I saw the tree was there,
but I just didn't realize it.

00:45:11.960 --> 00:45:14.750
So what I see in Buster
Keaton over and over

00:45:14.750 --> 00:45:18.360
is that way that the world
kind of changes around him,

00:45:18.360 --> 00:45:20.610
and then he has to come back
into consciousness of it.

00:45:20.610 --> 00:45:23.120
So in this case,
he is terribly shy.

00:45:23.120 --> 00:45:28.174
He really wants to
ask Mary to marry him.

00:45:28.174 --> 00:45:29.590
But he's never
been able to do it.

00:45:29.590 --> 00:45:34.500
So he decides to go off and
practice his proposal alone,

00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:36.563
as he feels he is alone.

