00:46:20.820 --> 00:46:23.190
But, yeah.

00:46:23.190 --> 00:46:27.240
So that moment of kind of
coming out of yourself, where

00:46:27.240 --> 00:46:31.170
the rehearsal becomes
real, for me, those

00:46:31.170 --> 00:46:34.260
are really fruitful spaces
to think about the way

00:46:34.260 --> 00:46:36.960
that this kind of
semi-distraction

00:46:36.960 --> 00:46:38.910
or attentiveness,
but attentiveness

00:46:38.910 --> 00:46:42.130
that lets your mind
be somewhere else,

00:46:42.130 --> 00:46:44.970
that that's what Keaton is
talking about and thinking

00:46:44.970 --> 00:46:45.480
about.

00:46:45.480 --> 00:46:47.850
And I don't know the
anthropologist you mentioned,

00:46:47.850 --> 00:46:49.950
Marina, but I really
should, because that

00:46:49.950 --> 00:46:52.260
question of detached
attentiveness,

00:46:52.260 --> 00:46:55.380
I think that's a lot of this,
that Keaton is out of the world

00:46:55.380 --> 00:46:56.920
and then back into it.

00:46:56.920 --> 00:47:00.880
So just quickly, I'm going to
maybe take five more minutes,

00:47:00.880 --> 00:47:02.790
let's say.

00:47:02.790 --> 00:47:05.490
All of these instances
here are cases

00:47:05.490 --> 00:47:10.290
of the kind of being out
and then coming back in.

00:47:10.290 --> 00:47:13.564
And there's another
Henry James quote, which

00:47:13.564 --> 00:47:14.730
I'm not going to talk about.

00:47:14.730 --> 00:47:17.310
But I just will say quickly
about The Ambassadors.

00:47:17.310 --> 00:47:21.350
I think The Ambassadors is full
of this, that Henry James uses

00:47:21.350 --> 00:47:24.790
free indirect discourse, great
creation of the 19th century

00:47:24.790 --> 00:47:25.290
novel.

00:47:25.290 --> 00:47:27.720
He uses free indirect
discourse to show people

00:47:27.720 --> 00:47:30.420
thinking that they
are in the world,

00:47:30.420 --> 00:47:32.610
and then discovering
that something is going

00:47:32.610 --> 00:47:35.910
on right next to them
that they had not heard,

00:47:35.910 --> 00:47:38.970
which in this case is expressed
"That indeed might be,

00:47:38.970 --> 00:47:40.840
but meanwhile,
she was going on,"

00:47:40.840 --> 00:47:43.770
which is a moment where we
realize that the character has

00:47:43.770 --> 00:47:46.650
been talking to us as if
he knew what was going on,

00:47:46.650 --> 00:47:49.410
but he's missed something
that the other character has

00:47:49.410 --> 00:47:50.280
said to him.

00:47:50.280 --> 00:47:52.110
So I think James
is really a master

00:47:52.110 --> 00:47:54.030
at thinking about that
way that when you think

00:47:54.030 --> 00:47:58.770
you're in and of this world, you
are actually also checked out

00:47:58.770 --> 00:47:59.670
of it.

00:47:59.670 --> 00:48:03.990
And then I'm going to just show
one other Buster Keaton clip.

00:48:03.990 --> 00:48:06.150
This is from a short
film called The Boat.

00:48:06.150 --> 00:48:12.990
And the point here is what
he is doing is decorating

00:48:12.990 --> 00:48:15.550
his cabin of the boat.

00:48:15.550 --> 00:48:18.230
And he is completely right to
want to decorate the cabin,

00:48:18.230 --> 00:48:20.730
because that's what one does
in a space that belongs to one.

00:48:20.730 --> 00:48:23.670
You just put up a painting,
and then you feel at home.

00:48:23.670 --> 00:48:26.730
But he's also completely
wrong, because he's in a boat,

00:48:26.730 --> 00:48:28.890
and the cabin is underwater.

00:48:28.890 --> 00:48:33.540
So the problem is double.

00:48:33.540 --> 00:48:35.280
It's a cabin, and
it's also the ocean.

00:48:35.280 --> 00:48:37.020
And then it's
complicated by the fact

00:48:37.020 --> 00:48:39.990
that the painting itself
is a painting of the ocean.

00:48:39.990 --> 00:48:42.960
So that's the kind of wrinkle
that kind of tells you

00:48:42.960 --> 00:48:44.490
the awareness of Keaton there.

00:48:44.490 --> 00:48:45.618
So here we go.

