00:49:17.580 --> 00:49:20.180
It's not so much, oh,
the wall is leaking,

00:49:20.180 --> 00:49:22.220
or, oh, there's water
coming out from behind it.

00:49:22.220 --> 00:49:26.740
It's that moment where
he touches the waves.

00:49:26.740 --> 00:49:28.570
Because that's the
moment where he's like,

00:49:28.570 --> 00:49:30.880
well, there is an
inexplicable water,

00:49:30.880 --> 00:49:32.420
and there's painting of water.

00:49:32.420 --> 00:49:34.570
So where am I here?

00:49:34.570 --> 00:49:37.600
And that moment of
shifting registers,

00:49:37.600 --> 00:49:42.250
like that location is, it's
really fascinating to me.

00:49:42.250 --> 00:49:44.740
I think that's the moment
where Keaton is thinking.

00:49:44.740 --> 00:49:48.790
And in that Sherlock
Junior, if you guys

00:49:48.790 --> 00:49:51.700
know that film, which is about
literally a projectionist who

00:49:51.700 --> 00:49:56.800
jumps into his own film, that's
a film that ends explicitly

00:49:56.800 --> 00:49:59.380
exploring this, because
the projectionist has

00:49:59.380 --> 00:50:03.640
to look at the picture of
two people kissing in order

00:50:03.640 --> 00:50:05.920
to understand that he
himself in his life,

00:50:05.920 --> 00:50:08.200
he ought to be kissing
the girl next to him.

00:50:08.200 --> 00:50:11.260
So it's a moment which makes
very explicit that this

00:50:11.260 --> 00:50:13.630
is about the shifting
of frames, and not

00:50:13.630 --> 00:50:15.860
knowing whether we belong
in one frame or another,

00:50:15.860 --> 00:50:18.370
but also discovering,
as Marina was saying,

00:50:18.370 --> 00:50:21.230
we belong in both at once.

