with the past, with respect

00:52:58.120 --> 00:53:00.370
to the issue of
distraction and attention,

00:53:00.370 --> 00:53:02.590
which is really in
contradistinction

00:53:02.590 --> 00:53:09.070
to many anxieties that are
currently being articulated

00:53:09.070 --> 00:53:10.760
around distraction.

00:53:10.760 --> 00:53:14.600
And I thought I would play
devil's advocate a little bit

00:53:14.600 --> 00:53:16.030
to test this.

00:53:16.030 --> 00:53:19.030
And actually I'll start,
Marina, with your book,

00:53:19.030 --> 00:53:21.010
because there's a
lot of ambivalence

00:53:21.010 --> 00:53:24.940
in your book around
continuity and discontinuity,

00:53:24.940 --> 00:53:27.400
and whether or not the
forms of distraction

00:53:27.400 --> 00:53:32.830
that we find in our many
forms of electronic mediation

00:53:32.830 --> 00:53:36.100
really are the same
as or different

00:53:36.100 --> 00:53:39.580
from the forms of
distraction which

00:53:39.580 --> 00:53:43.130
many of the authors
you cite are praising

00:53:43.130 --> 00:53:45.580
in fascinating
and engaging ways.

00:53:45.580 --> 00:53:50.050
So I wonder if also part of this
is a question of nomenclature.

00:53:50.050 --> 00:53:53.020
I mean, when you make the
move from, say, distraction

00:53:53.020 --> 00:53:58.240
to reverie, do you suddenly
have to discount certain things

00:53:58.240 --> 00:54:00.370
that you would include
within distraction,

00:54:00.370 --> 00:54:03.484
