00:54:49.270 --> 00:54:50.260
You can.

00:54:50.260 --> 00:54:53.470
Well, no, I mean, of
course there's something

00:54:53.470 --> 00:54:57.490
very disingenuous about
my book, because I

00:54:57.490 --> 00:55:02.350
suffer immensely from the
fear of being distracted.

00:55:02.350 --> 00:55:07.150
And I've always been a
very distracted person.

00:55:07.150 --> 00:55:09.760
And I was going to tell
an anecdote, which is

00:55:09.760 --> 00:55:12.400
so personal, and so unacademic.

00:55:12.400 --> 00:55:12.910
Should I?

00:55:12.910 --> 00:55:13.720
Yes, yes.

00:55:13.720 --> 00:55:17.140
All right this is basically
shirking the question.

00:55:17.140 --> 00:55:20.500
But about 10 years
ago, when I still

00:55:20.500 --> 00:55:24.970
had use of the Harvard
University Health Services,

00:55:24.970 --> 00:55:26.540
I had a bad headache.

00:55:26.540 --> 00:55:28.870
So I went, and I got an MRI.

00:55:28.870 --> 00:55:31.180
And the doctor sat me
down, and he said, well,

00:55:31.180 --> 00:55:32.950
I have very, very bad news.

00:55:32.950 --> 00:55:36.451
There's a whole part of
your brain that is missing.

00:55:36.451 --> 00:55:39.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:39.280 --> 00:55:44.110
I tottered out of the
doctor, and I thought, well,

00:55:44.110 --> 00:55:47.440
I'm going to think of
this in a different way.

00:55:47.440 --> 00:55:51.310
All right, I have part of
my brain that's missing.

00:55:51.310 --> 00:55:53.100
