00:56:26.270 --> 00:56:30.250
So about a month later, the
guy called me back, and said,

00:56:30.250 --> 00:56:31.120
don't worry.

00:56:31.120 --> 00:56:32.810
Everything's OK.

00:56:32.810 --> 00:56:37.400
But in the meantime, I
thought about this a lot.

00:56:37.400 --> 00:56:41.755
And I thought, well, we
all have certain problems.

00:56:44.420 --> 00:56:46.870
I've always been a
very distracted person.

00:56:46.870 --> 00:56:52.450
I mean, I was a terrible
student in early years.

00:56:52.450 --> 00:56:56.020
And so I gravitated
towards those things

00:56:56.020 --> 00:56:59.230
that were more of the reverie--

00:56:59.230 --> 00:57:02.530
for example your question,
what happens when someone asked

00:57:02.530 --> 00:57:04.840
me a question with
the word nomenclature,

00:57:04.840 --> 00:57:07.480
my brain closes instantly.

00:57:07.480 --> 00:57:09.730
So it was like the
X-ray was right,

00:57:09.730 --> 00:57:13.360
because the word
"nomenclature" completely

00:57:13.360 --> 00:57:15.310
makes my brain turn off.

00:57:15.310 --> 00:57:18.940
But so what I'm trying
to talk about in the book

00:57:18.940 --> 00:57:22.780
is how there are
certain ways we have

00:57:22.780 --> 00:57:26.860
to understand a weakness
that is actually a strength.

00:57:26.860 --> 00:57:28.870
And I think what
John does in his book

00:57:28.870 --> 00:57:32.860
that I felt very, very
close to is understanding

00:57:32.860 --> 00:57:35.860
what does fiction do for us.

00:57:35.860 --> 00:57:40.720
And we know that Don
Quixote is not real.

00:57:40.720 --> 00:57:44.220
And you were quoting
Gallagher as saying,

00:57:44.220 --> 00:57:49.560
we don't love Don
Quixote because he's--

00:57:49.560 --> 00:57:50.820
how does it go?

00:57:50.820 --> 00:57:55.240
It's because it's a fiction
that we're drawn to it.

00:57:55.240 --> 00:57:57.640
We're drawn to the unreal.

00:57:57.640 --> 00:58:01.540
We're helped in
our world by a kind

00:58:01.540 --> 00:58:04.900
of consciousness of unreality.

00:58:04.900 --> 00:58:09.590
And to me, the way that I can't
quite think in a straight line,

00:58:09.590 --> 00:58:13.450
I can't think about
a nomenclature ever,

00:58:13.450 --> 00:58:19.000
actually has helped me be very
receptive to other things,

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:23.260
and especially to fiction, and
especially to all the quotes

00:58:23.260 --> 00:58:25.930
that you have from
the Victorian novel.

00:58:25.930 --> 00:58:27.820
So that was a non-response.

00:58:27.820 --> 00:58:31.120
But at least you know
about my brain, now.

00:58:31.120 --> 00:58:32.690
I think that's personal.

00:58:32.690 --> 00:58:34.769
But it's kind of a great story.

00:58:34.769 --> 00:58:35.560
It's a great story.

00:58:35.560 --> 00:58:36.550
It's a great story.

00:58:36.550 --> 00:58:38.100
So can I pick up
the history angle?

00:58:38.100 --> 00:58:38.910
Yeah, sure.

00:58:38.910 --> 00:58:40.374
Thank God.

00:58:40.374 --> 00:58:42.790
So that phrase that you were
talking about from Gallagher,

00:58:42.790 --> 00:58:46.180
I think it's believable stories
that do not command belief.

00:58:46.180 --> 00:58:48.250
And so that's interesting
way of thinking

00:58:48.250 --> 00:58:49.960
about something
that could be true,

00:58:49.960 --> 00:58:51.290
but does not claim to be true.

00:58:51.290 --> 00:58:52.810
And I totally agree
with what you're

00:58:52.810 --> 00:58:56.330
saying, that that is the
interesting gray space.

00:58:56.330 --> 00:58:59.200
But the fact that
you have fiction

00:58:59.200 --> 00:59:02.080
doing that in the
18th century, the fact

00:59:02.080 --> 00:59:05.350
that Florence Nightingale
spends a lot of time complaining

00:59:05.350 --> 00:59:07.670
about what a sketchy
age we live in.

00:59:07.670 --> 00:59:09.520
We live in the
age of the sketch,

00:59:09.520 --> 00:59:11.060
where nothing is
serious anymore.

00:59:11.060 --> 00:59:12.070
Everything jumps around.

00:59:12.070 --> 00:59:15.880
That does kind of make
me feel that there's

00:59:15.880 --> 00:59:19.470
a pattern of novelty that we can
trace back a really long way.

00:59:19.470 --> 00:59:22.360
And what the actual
novelty is is different.

00:59:22.360 --> 00:59:26.780
But kind of the attack wave
of those cultural shifts,

00:59:26.780 --> 00:59:29.600
or technological shifts, I
think there is some similarity

00:59:29.600 --> 00:59:32.140
in the attack wave.

00:59:32.140 --> 00:59:33.950
But I totally take
the point, also,

00:59:33.950 --> 00:59:38.000
that the affordances of one
age, like the affordance

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:42.110
of the printing press, or
the performance of the radio,

00:59:42.110 --> 00:59:45.080
or film, which obviously
was, in its day,

00:59:45.080 --> 00:59:47.630
seemed terribly
distracting to people.

00:59:47.630 --> 00:59:50.600
But the affordance is still
different from the affordance

00:59:50.600 --> 00:59:51.440
of the internet.

00:59:51.440 --> 00:59:57.050
Yeah, there's a wonderful piece
by Krakauer called "Boredom."

00:59:57.050 --> 01:00:02.510
And horrified, the idea
that all these neon signs

01:00:02.510 --> 01:00:05.510
and the radio, all
these are taking us away

01:00:05.510 --> 01:00:12.080
from the kind of Pascalian space
of existential consciousness.

01:00:12.080 --> 01:00:15.230
And when I disparaged
Heidegger, it's

01:00:15.230 --> 01:00:19.310
only because I spent so
many months of my life

01:00:19.310 --> 01:00:23.390
reading Heidegger, and
going into this kind

01:00:23.390 --> 01:00:28.760
of masochistic
concentration tunnel,

01:00:28.760 --> 01:00:31.230
and then getting out
of that and thinking,

01:00:31.230 --> 01:00:34.550
why am I doing this to myself?

01:00:34.550 --> 01:00:36.320
It's not really me.

01:00:36.320 --> 01:00:40.910
It's a kind of
nomenclature of something.

01:00:40.910 --> 01:00:43.550
So I think, of course,
it's not a new thing.

01:00:43.550 --> 01:00:48.590
But we are in a moment of
extreme anxiety about our lack

01:00:48.590 --> 01:00:49.520
of concentration.

01:00:49.520 --> 01:00:52.169
But to take it even
closer to home,

01:00:52.169 --> 01:00:54.710
it'd be interesting to poll the
room and see if people agree.

01:00:54.710 --> 01:00:57.890
But I was thinking about
the way the telephone worked

01:00:57.890 --> 01:00:58.700
as a technology.

01:00:58.700 --> 01:01:01.250
When we were kids it
drove our parents crazy,

01:01:01.250 --> 01:01:03.510
because we're all supposed
to be here as a family,

01:01:03.510 --> 01:01:06.390
and you have the telephone,
and it allows you, essentially,

01:01:06.390 --> 01:01:07.400
to surf the web.

01:01:07.400 --> 01:01:09.200
By calling your
friend, you are surfing

01:01:09.200 --> 01:01:10.310
the web of your friends.

01:01:10.310 --> 01:01:14.360
And now the telephone is
just this horrible old people

01:01:14.360 --> 01:01:16.100
technology that people hate.

01:01:16.100 --> 01:01:18.290
Nobody wants to talk
on the phone anymore

01:01:18.290 --> 01:01:19.130
below a certain age.

01:01:19.130 --> 01:01:20.465
The parents are saying, why
don't you phone your friends

01:01:20.465 --> 01:01:20.965
anymore?

01:01:20.965 --> 01:01:23.499
Yeah, exactly, because phoning
would be a form of presence.

01:01:23.499 --> 01:01:25.040
And it would be real
and qualitative.

01:01:25.040 --> 01:01:27.440
But OK, but 35 years
ago, that's not

01:01:27.440 --> 01:01:30.020
what people thought
the phone was.

01:01:30.020 --> 01:01:32.150
So I definitely think
we're in a new age.

01:01:32.150 --> 01:01:38.020
I just wonder if it's
newly new, or if it's

01:01:38.020 --> 01:01:39.650
just kind of oldly new.

01:01:39.650 --> 01:01:42.750
Yeah, I can certainly see that.

01:01:42.750 --> 01:01:46.450
But I think that my
experience as a teacher

01:01:46.450 --> 01:01:50.020
is that there have definitely
been changes in the way

01:01:50.020 --> 01:01:55.390
that attention is mobilized
by students, or not mobilized.

01:01:55.390 --> 01:01:58.120
And I had an interesting
experience a few years ago

01:01:58.120 --> 01:02:00.610
when I was teaching
a tutorial, and we

01:02:00.610 --> 01:02:03.250
read Bachelard's The
Poetics of Space.

01:02:03.250 --> 01:02:05.080
And there's passages--
beautiful passages.

01:02:05.080 --> 01:02:09.890
You cite the book in
your book, Marina, where

01:02:09.890 --> 01:02:12.310
he's talking about boredom.

01:02:12.310 --> 01:02:16.060
And my three students
could not understand what

01:02:16.060 --> 01:02:17.440
Bachelard was talking about.

01:02:17.440 --> 01:02:20.530
I mean, literally seemed like
they could not understand

01:02:20.530 --> 01:02:22.180
what this experience was.

01:02:22.180 --> 01:02:26.560
And for me, it was a
moment of, oh, your world

01:02:26.560 --> 01:02:28.630
is quite different from
the one I grew up in,

01:02:28.630 --> 01:02:30.730
in which it is very
easy for me to remember

01:02:30.730 --> 01:02:34.720
boredom of a kind that resembles
what Bachelard describes,

01:02:34.720 --> 01:02:35.410
right?

01:02:35.410 --> 01:02:38.620
So partly I'm less interested
in the anxiety about loss

01:02:38.620 --> 01:02:41.620
of attention than I am
interested in the forms

01:02:41.620 --> 01:02:44.740
that distraction takes,
the extent to which they're

01:02:44.740 --> 01:02:48.610
commodified at a much
accelerated rate now.

01:02:48.610 --> 01:02:51.550
I mean, I guess I'm thinking
of Jonathan Crary's 24/7

01:02:51.550 --> 01:02:53.080
kind of thing.

01:02:53.080 --> 01:02:56.860
And just, it's not a kind of
this has never happened before.

01:02:56.860 --> 01:02:59.740
But nonetheless,
just as Buster Keaton

01:02:59.740 --> 01:03:03.310
is working with audiences
to get them to understand

01:03:03.310 --> 01:03:05.260
how to handle the
problems of attention

01:03:05.260 --> 01:03:08.680
in the moment when film emerges,
that we are kind of looking

01:03:08.680 --> 01:03:12.550
for models of how to handle
the forms of attention

01:03:12.550 --> 01:03:14.035
and distraction
that are available

01:03:14.035 --> 01:03:16.540
or not available to us now.

01:03:16.540 --> 01:03:18.250
I totally agree with that point.

01:03:18.250 --> 01:03:20.350
I remember the first
time I saw people

01:03:20.350 --> 01:03:24.190
who do these poetic
experiments using, I think,

01:03:24.190 --> 01:03:25.390
is it called Shockwave?

01:03:25.390 --> 01:03:27.666
Like Flash players
that you can't control.

01:03:27.666 --> 01:03:30.040
Where you go onto the internet,
and the poem just kind of

01:03:30.040 --> 01:03:32.530
comes at you.

01:03:32.530 --> 01:03:34.240
And I think of
that as an attempt

01:03:34.240 --> 01:03:37.060
to cognitively
reckon with what does

01:03:37.060 --> 01:03:40.300
it mean to be
immersed in this way,

01:03:40.300 --> 01:03:43.887
and discover that turning on
and off might seem to be easy,

01:03:43.887 --> 01:03:45.220
but it's actually not that easy.

01:03:45.220 --> 01:03:46.630
So, yeah.

01:03:46.630 --> 01:03:47.530
I think that's right.

01:03:47.530 --> 01:03:48.030
Yeah.

01:03:48.030 --> 01:03:54.190
Are we worried that we have
too much focus, really?

01:03:54.190 --> 01:03:58.510
Because we're always
looking for something.

01:03:58.510 --> 01:04:00.070
We're expecting something.

01:04:00.070 --> 01:04:05.800
We need the
adrenaline, the high.

01:04:05.800 --> 01:04:09.880
Even getting some stupid
text from someone we hate,

01:04:09.880 --> 01:04:12.986
it's still some kind of high.

01:04:12.986 --> 01:04:14.860
You have a wonderful
expression in your book,

01:04:14.860 --> 01:04:18.070
"Pavlovian creatures
of the internet."

01:04:18.070 --> 01:04:19.120
Yeah, we are.

01:04:22.660 --> 01:04:27.040
I mean, it kills me that
my students are so unhappy,

01:04:27.040 --> 01:04:29.890
because on one level
they're on their Adderall,

01:04:29.890 --> 01:04:30.730
and their Ritalin.

01:04:30.730 --> 01:04:32.140
And it does help them.

01:04:32.140 --> 01:04:35.560
It makes them
write maybe faster.

01:04:35.560 --> 01:04:39.610
But they're feeling
they're mourning something

01:04:39.610 --> 01:04:42.010
that they don't really
know what they're mourning,

01:04:42.010 --> 01:04:44.600
because it's not boredom.

01:04:44.600 --> 01:04:46.790
It's something else.

01:04:46.790 --> 01:04:48.220
I'm not sure what.

01:04:48.220 --> 01:04:49.870
Can I put in a plug
for-- do you know

01:04:49.870 --> 01:04:54.170
this new book, My Year of
Rest and Relaxation, Moshfegh.

01:04:54.170 --> 01:04:56.156
So I'm only halfway
through now, so it

01:04:56.156 --> 01:04:57.280
might turn out to be wrong.

01:04:57.280 --> 01:05:00.520
But it's about somebody
who cannot find that place

01:05:00.520 --> 01:05:02.480
of solitude and downtime.

01:05:02.480 --> 01:05:05.140
And so she medicates
herself to achieve

01:05:05.140 --> 01:05:07.480
it, which obviously
has all sorts

01:05:07.480 --> 01:05:09.400
of counterproductive results.

01:05:09.400 --> 01:05:12.610
But it's this notion that,
what's the Conrad line?

01:05:12.610 --> 01:05:14.860
"In the destructive
element, immerse."

01:05:14.860 --> 01:05:16.337
You can't go out.

01:05:16.337 --> 01:05:17.920
I mean, it would be
impossible for her

01:05:17.920 --> 01:05:20.620
to imagine just, oh, I'll go
sit on a farm for a while.

01:05:20.620 --> 01:05:25.540
But maybe I can pharmacopeize
my way back to that state.

01:05:25.540 --> 01:05:26.780
It's fascinating.

01:05:26.780 --> 01:05:30.430
And that is a book that seems
to me to be encountering

01:05:30.430 --> 01:05:33.858
the new qualitative situation.

01:05:33.858 --> 01:05:35.260
[INAUDIBLE]

01:05:35.260 --> 01:05:38.240
My Year of Rest and Relaxation.

01:05:38.240 --> 01:05:39.460
Yeah.

01:05:39.460 --> 01:05:44.640
I loved how in your book
there's some wonderful quotes.

01:05:44.640 --> 01:05:51.640
So John, for instance, contrasts
Lord Jim and Our Mutual Friend,

01:05:51.640 --> 01:05:52.840
these two passages.

01:05:52.840 --> 01:05:56.920
And in Lord Jim, Lord
Jim is Conrad's character

01:05:56.920 --> 01:06:01.630
is reading about these
sentimental novels

01:06:01.630 --> 01:06:06.820
where characters save
heroically somebody else.

01:06:06.820 --> 01:06:10.360
And he's so immersed in
this that when he actually

01:06:10.360 --> 01:06:13.450
needs to come up on
deck and save someone,

01:06:13.450 --> 01:06:17.770
nobody's home, because he's
just completely focused,

01:06:17.770 --> 01:06:21.220
concentrated on that moment.

01:06:21.220 --> 01:06:26.830
Whereas in Our Mutual Friend,
Lizzie Hexam manages--

01:06:26.830 --> 01:06:28.790
she sees a man drowning.

01:06:28.790 --> 01:06:32.560
And I was thinking of Camus's
The Fall, the famous beginning

01:06:32.560 --> 01:06:34.960
of the book.

01:06:34.960 --> 01:06:38.170
But she sees someone
drowning, and she

01:06:38.170 --> 01:06:42.190
manages to have two things
happening at the same time,

01:06:42.190 --> 01:06:44.980
two emotions-- fear
but this courage.

01:06:44.980 --> 01:06:46.895
It's "I don't know
this person, but I'm

01:06:46.895 --> 01:06:48.020
going to save this person."

01:06:48.020 --> 01:06:51.430
And as she's praying,
she's praying,

01:06:51.430 --> 01:06:53.560
she's hoping that
this is not happening,

01:06:53.560 --> 01:06:57.480
she goes and dives in the water
and actually saves the person.

01:06:57.480 --> 01:07:00.010
And for me this was
a wonderful example

01:07:00.010 --> 01:07:04.750
of how we can do
many things at once.

01:07:04.750 --> 01:07:12.520
And thank god we can have this
presence/absence gift, really.

01:07:12.520 --> 01:07:14.860
Because, as Hume would
say, if we're just

01:07:14.860 --> 01:07:17.860
thinking about Descartes,
or if we're just

01:07:17.860 --> 01:07:20.920
doing what Heidegger would
like us to do, and plunge

01:07:20.920 --> 01:07:25.030
into this kind of
important boredom,

01:07:25.030 --> 01:07:31.270
we're not going to be able
to cull the kind of magic

01:07:31.270 --> 01:07:35.170
of the detailed
magic of the things

01:07:35.170 --> 01:07:37.040
that don't seem to matter.

01:07:37.040 --> 01:07:40.780
I always think of Mrs.
Ramsay in To the Lighthouse.

01:07:40.780 --> 01:07:44.230
You look at her life,
and it's a series of kind

01:07:44.230 --> 01:07:46.870
of not very important events.

01:07:46.870 --> 01:07:51.220
But those events make
her that full person,

01:07:51.220 --> 01:07:53.770
that person who's
capable of loving,

01:07:53.770 --> 01:07:56.470
of noticing, of nurturing.

01:07:56.470 --> 01:07:59.620
And Mr. Ramsay, who
wants to go from A to Z,

01:07:59.620 --> 01:08:01.660
and to understand
all philosophy,

01:08:01.660 --> 01:08:04.720
is incapable of
being with anybody.

01:08:04.720 --> 01:08:08.650
So it's because of Mrs.
Ramsay's inattention

01:08:08.650 --> 01:08:15.710
that she's actually so
receptive to her fellow humans.

01:08:15.710 --> 01:08:21.080
And speaking of being
receptive to fellow humans,

01:08:21.080 --> 01:08:24.229
I think it's a good opportunity
to open the conversation up

01:08:24.229 --> 01:08:25.220
to everybody here.

01:08:25.220 --> 01:08:26.670
So there's a couple of my mics.

01:08:26.670 --> 01:08:27.920
No nomenclature, please.

01:08:27.920 --> 01:08:28.460
No.

01:08:28.460 --> 01:08:30.830
No nomenclature.

01:08:30.830 --> 01:08:36.649
And you can share your MRI, but
only if the story ends well.

01:08:36.649 --> 01:08:37.380
There are mics.

01:08:37.380 --> 01:08:40.108
So I see two hands
up in the center.

01:08:44.370 --> 01:08:47.069
Samantha, why don't you
go first, and then Martin?

01:08:47.069 --> 01:08:50.529
Thank you both for
just really rich topic.

01:08:50.529 --> 01:08:54.300
So as a philosopher,
I'm going to ask

01:08:54.300 --> 01:08:56.350
a philosophical question.

01:08:56.350 --> 01:09:00.640
So let's suppose distraction
is a kind of good.

01:09:00.640 --> 01:09:02.939
There's a question of
what kind of good is it.

01:09:02.939 --> 01:09:06.000
So there is these certain
instances of I'm Hume,

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:08.520
and I'm trying to
bring down Descartes,

01:09:08.520 --> 01:09:10.979
and so going down to
the pub with my friends

01:09:10.979 --> 01:09:12.770
is a nice kind of distraction.

01:09:12.770 --> 01:09:16.620
So then I can come back, and I
can really show why he's wrong.

01:09:16.620 --> 01:09:20.819
So that's an instrumental view
of the goodness of distraction.

01:09:20.819 --> 01:09:22.560
But then it's
interesting to then think

01:09:22.560 --> 01:09:24.250
about the case of art, right?

01:09:24.250 --> 01:09:26.880
And so what has Darwin
lost, or the examples, John,

01:09:26.880 --> 01:09:28.290
that you were talking about.

01:09:28.290 --> 01:09:30.779
When we are in this
distracted mode.

01:09:30.779 --> 01:09:34.081
It's less clear that that just
has this instrumental value

01:09:34.081 --> 01:09:34.580
there.

01:09:34.580 --> 01:09:39.180
It seems distraction is more
of an intrinsically good state

01:09:39.180 --> 01:09:39.840
to be in.

01:09:39.840 --> 01:09:42.210
So I just want to invite
you to say a little bit more

01:09:42.210 --> 01:09:45.120
about if you have thoughts about
what kind of a good distraction

01:09:45.120 --> 01:09:45.620
is.

01:09:45.620 --> 01:09:46.979
Is it an instrumental good?

01:09:46.979 --> 01:09:50.084
Is it an intrinsic good?

01:09:50.084 --> 01:09:51.000
Can I take that first?

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:51.479
Yeah.

01:09:51.479 --> 01:09:52.500
I'm really glad
you mentioned that,

01:09:52.500 --> 01:09:54.300
because when you were,
Marina, when you were talking

01:09:54.300 --> 01:09:56.008
about Darwin, I was
thinking that there's

01:09:56.008 --> 01:09:57.552
another 19th century
example, which

01:09:57.552 --> 01:09:59.010
I'm sure you were
thinking of, too,

01:09:59.010 --> 01:10:03.090
which is John Stuart Mill has
this mental breakdown, in which

01:10:03.090 --> 01:10:06.550
he recuperates from
by way of Coleridge.

01:10:06.550 --> 01:10:10.830
And he really does kind of
try to unpack that problem,

01:10:10.830 --> 01:10:13.500
whether what he
needed was simply

01:10:13.500 --> 01:10:17.080
to be able to turn off
the utilitarian brain.

01:10:17.080 --> 01:10:21.420
That would be the account that
Bentham is good, but just not

01:10:21.420 --> 01:10:22.350
all the time.

01:10:22.350 --> 01:10:25.590
You need some commercials,
too, or something.

01:10:25.590 --> 01:10:28.920
But he ends up coming
down more on the notion

01:10:28.920 --> 01:10:30.264
that there is this other thing.

01:10:30.264 --> 01:10:32.430
Which I'm not sure if he
uses the word "experience"?

01:10:32.430 --> 01:10:34.140
I have to go back to
Martin Jay's book.

01:10:34.140 --> 01:10:36.330
But I mean I feel
like the point there

01:10:36.330 --> 01:10:39.900
is that he's trying to get at
something where what he likes

01:10:39.900 --> 01:10:41.760
about Coleridge's
poetry as distinct

01:10:41.760 --> 01:10:43.560
from other romantic
poetry is that it

01:10:43.560 --> 01:10:45.600
fuses thought and feeling.

01:10:45.600 --> 01:10:49.840
So by Mills's account
there is this other thing,

01:10:49.840 --> 01:10:52.110
which is that it
makes you grapple

01:10:52.110 --> 01:10:55.915
with the difficulty of the fact
that though I'm in my mind,

01:10:55.915 --> 01:10:57.540
having this one
thought and experience,

01:10:57.540 --> 01:11:01.110
somebody else out there is
experiencing differently.

01:11:01.110 --> 01:11:03.720
And I can, yes,
somewhat apprehend it,

01:11:03.720 --> 01:11:07.020
because poetry somewhat
brings me into their world.

01:11:07.020 --> 01:11:11.460
But imagination doesn't
take me all the way.

01:11:11.460 --> 01:11:13.710
So I think, if I'm understanding
your question right,

01:11:13.710 --> 01:11:17.580
I think what I'm saying is not
just that imagination becomes

01:11:17.580 --> 01:11:20.609
like a cure-all
panacea, like when

01:11:20.609 --> 01:11:21.900
we have an artistic experience.

01:11:21.900 --> 01:11:28.142
It has this great utility of it
gives us a secret passageway.

01:11:28.142 --> 01:11:29.850
It's actually more
complicated than that.

01:11:29.850 --> 01:11:33.330
It's that the
aesthetic experience,

01:11:33.330 --> 01:11:37.830
like trying to catch the eye
of that Caravaggio character,

01:11:37.830 --> 01:11:40.910
is at once a payoff.

01:11:40.910 --> 01:11:42.260
There's some sensual beauty.

01:11:42.260 --> 01:11:43.520
There's some apprehension.

01:11:43.520 --> 01:11:44.990
There's something you get.

01:11:44.990 --> 01:11:47.360
And there's also a sense
of distance as well.

01:11:47.360 --> 01:11:50.120
So I think to me that's--
do you know what I'm saying?

01:11:50.120 --> 01:11:53.540
The utility in a way is that
it's a qualitatively different

01:11:53.540 --> 01:11:54.757
kind of utility.

01:11:57.560 --> 01:11:59.530
Marina, do you want
to weigh in on this?

01:11:59.530 --> 01:12:01.980
Because you talk about
that paradox in your book.

01:12:01.980 --> 01:12:02.520
Yeah.

01:12:02.520 --> 01:12:06.360
I mean, the presence
absence thing, I

01:12:06.360 --> 01:12:09.010
mean I was mentioning
briefly Nietzsche,

01:12:09.010 --> 01:12:12.360
and how he would say, I
can only really produce

01:12:12.360 --> 01:12:15.480
these thoughts when
I'm losing myself,

01:12:15.480 --> 01:12:17.330
when I'm not going
in a straight line.

01:12:17.330 --> 01:12:22.590
And so again, I always
feel a little bit

01:12:22.590 --> 01:12:26.640
disingenuous with this whole
topic, because of course I

01:12:26.640 --> 01:12:35.190
want to have the richest, most
intense philosophical life

01:12:35.190 --> 01:12:39.180
possible, despite or
because of the distraction.

01:12:39.180 --> 01:12:43.440
And actually, I
mean, I don't know

01:12:43.440 --> 01:12:46.080
how to put it, that
the presence/absence,

01:12:46.080 --> 01:12:49.620
that this anthropologist
who tells us

01:12:49.620 --> 01:12:54.210
said we couldn't live
if we lived simply

01:12:54.210 --> 01:12:56.540
in the mode of presence.

01:12:56.540 --> 01:13:01.200
And so we have to absent
ourselves from depth in order

01:13:01.200 --> 01:13:04.530
to get to a greater depth.

01:13:04.530 --> 01:13:07.710
And it's hard to
explain, but I really

01:13:07.710 --> 01:13:12.150
understand that,
how sometimes, I

01:13:12.150 --> 01:13:14.430
mean, when you're
talking with someone,

01:13:14.430 --> 01:13:16.830
and you hear someone
else's conversation,

01:13:16.830 --> 01:13:20.490
and you kind of are dying
to listen to that other day

01:13:20.490 --> 01:13:22.350
dichotic listening it's called.

01:13:22.350 --> 01:13:24.720
And we're all guilty of that.

01:13:24.720 --> 01:13:30.600
But it happens also when we're
watching, say, Breaking Bad.

01:13:30.600 --> 01:13:31.860
I don't know how many people--

01:13:31.860 --> 01:13:33.780
everyone has watched Breaking.

01:13:33.780 --> 01:13:37.050
I never feel guilty when
I'm watching Breaking Bad,

01:13:37.050 --> 01:13:42.210
because I'm actually completely
ensconced in a fictional world.

01:13:42.210 --> 01:13:49.820
I feel guilty when I feel that
I am basically I'm not together.

01:13:49.820 --> 01:13:52.390
I'm pressing this one button.

01:13:52.390 --> 01:13:54.990
I'm half-looking at one thing.

01:13:54.990 --> 01:13:58.860
So for the philosopher,
I think the philosopher

01:13:58.860 --> 01:14:05.640
wants a certain amount of
lost time in order to find

01:14:05.640 --> 01:14:09.210
the time that will be
the time that will allow

01:14:09.210 --> 01:14:11.980
them to write or to create.

01:14:11.980 --> 01:14:15.440
So I think it has a
connection to creativity.

01:14:15.440 --> 01:14:17.790
I don't know.

01:14:17.790 --> 01:14:19.670
Martin.

01:14:19.670 --> 01:14:24.220
So I may be totally wrong, but
I'd like to know what this is.

01:14:24.220 --> 01:14:28.650
I think Robin, in your
question, this was distraction.

01:14:28.650 --> 01:14:30.770
I'm asking you a question,
but at the same time,

01:14:30.770 --> 01:14:31.870
I'm looking something up.

01:14:31.870 --> 01:14:34.480
And no one can pay
attention anymore

01:14:34.480 --> 01:14:36.690
because they're so distracted.

01:14:36.690 --> 01:14:40.150
Marina, I felt like for you,
this was not distraction,

01:14:40.150 --> 01:14:41.440
but total absorption.

01:14:41.440 --> 01:14:44.090
I'm looking at it, and
I forget where I am.

01:14:44.090 --> 01:14:45.760
And I'm looking at it only.

01:14:45.760 --> 01:14:48.950
So I would like to
know which it is.

01:14:48.950 --> 01:14:51.079
And since there is
this discrepancy here,

01:14:51.079 --> 01:14:53.370
maybe, I think John is right,
and it's semi-detachment.

01:14:53.370 --> 01:14:55.700
[LAUGHTER]

01:14:55.700 --> 01:14:58.180
But I am glad you asked
that, because something

01:14:58.180 --> 01:15:01.640
in John's book, I think it's the
only thing I disagreed with--

01:15:01.640 --> 01:15:02.140
Oh, good.

01:15:02.140 --> 01:15:08.710
--is you talk about this
person who is in a cafe,

01:15:08.710 --> 01:15:11.890
and I forget who
it is, in a cafe,

01:15:11.890 --> 01:15:15.040
and basically is
feeling terribly guilty,

01:15:15.040 --> 01:15:18.610
because instead of partaking
into the conversation,

01:15:18.610 --> 01:15:21.760
he's actually doing stuff that
we know when our students are

01:15:21.760 --> 01:15:23.290
pretending to scratch their--

01:15:25.870 --> 01:15:27.700
I see what you're doing.

01:15:27.700 --> 01:15:28.750
You're not listening.

01:15:28.750 --> 01:15:30.680
You're actually
looking at your iPhone,

01:15:30.680 --> 01:15:32.950
which is hiding in your shoe.

01:15:32.950 --> 01:15:37.600
And so in your book,
and I have it somewhere,

01:15:37.600 --> 01:15:41.180
he defends himself, or you,
John, defend him by saying,

01:15:41.180 --> 01:15:46.960
well, actually he has access to
the in-between at that moment.

01:15:46.960 --> 01:15:48.910
But I actually don't
think it's true.

01:15:48.910 --> 01:15:54.390
I think the in-between
comes when we float,

01:15:54.390 --> 01:15:58.150
we daydream, we get lost.

01:15:58.150 --> 01:16:02.020
But the phone for me
is total absorption.

01:16:02.020 --> 01:16:07.270
And I have to say what I'm
looking in my shoe as well--

01:16:07.270 --> 01:16:09.420
I've done it, too--

01:16:09.420 --> 01:16:12.020
I'm lost to the
rest of the world.

01:16:12.020 --> 01:16:13.510
And that's what I hate.

01:16:13.510 --> 01:16:16.730
I hate that I'm no
longer receptive.

01:16:16.730 --> 01:16:20.260
I'm actually
absolutely directed.

01:16:20.260 --> 01:16:24.010
So for me, that little
thing is the direction

01:16:24.010 --> 01:16:25.090
that I don't want.

01:16:25.090 --> 01:16:27.800
I don't want to be like that.

01:16:27.800 --> 01:16:32.740
I want to be able to
half-understand maybe

01:16:32.740 --> 01:16:35.680
a conversation, but
not completely be

01:16:35.680 --> 01:16:40.480
able to turn into a
monk of the iPhone.

01:16:40.480 --> 01:16:43.372
That's our desert, there.

01:16:43.372 --> 01:16:45.870
Marina, have you ever seen that
movie Pillow Talk, the Rock

01:16:45.870 --> 01:16:46.370
Hudson--

01:16:46.370 --> 01:16:48.060
Of course, with
the feet, and the--

01:16:48.060 --> 01:16:49.120
Yeah.

01:16:49.120 --> 01:16:50.850
Because that seems
like it's about that,

01:16:50.850 --> 01:16:54.340
the phone having that quality.

01:16:54.340 --> 01:16:56.530
So in my role as
splitting, as being

01:16:56.530 --> 01:16:59.170
the synthesis, or Aufhebung.

01:16:59.170 --> 01:17:01.540
I think the word
I would go back to

01:17:01.540 --> 01:17:06.440
is the word affordance there,
meaning that cognitively

01:17:06.440 --> 01:17:08.440
there's just all sorts
of tools and technologies

01:17:08.440 --> 01:17:11.020
that hit the human species.

01:17:11.020 --> 01:17:13.660
And they each allow
different capacities.

01:17:13.660 --> 01:17:15.880
And Marina, I think
you're right in saying

01:17:15.880 --> 01:17:19.214
that for you the affordance
is allowing you the window in.

01:17:19.214 --> 01:17:21.130
But Robin, I think you're
also right in saying

01:17:21.130 --> 01:17:25.390
that you watch people get
glimmers and distraction.

01:17:25.390 --> 01:17:27.940
And that's my experience of
how my teens use their iPhones.

01:17:27.940 --> 01:17:30.960
It's terrifying to me.

01:17:30.960 --> 01:17:32.710
They put down books
and picked up iPhones.

01:17:32.710 --> 01:17:35.160
And that's what they do.

01:17:35.160 --> 01:17:37.780
So Martin, I mean, that's
an unsatisfying answer.

01:17:37.780 --> 01:17:39.950
But it's a tool like any other.

01:17:39.950 --> 01:17:42.700
And it's a tool
that can kick you

01:17:42.700 --> 01:17:43.910
in a bunch of different ways.

01:17:43.910 --> 01:17:46.150
And I think what I was
trying to argue at the end,

01:17:46.150 --> 01:17:47.680
but it's not a
fully-formed thought,

01:17:47.680 --> 01:17:50.560
is that I was making
the case that sometimes

01:17:50.560 --> 01:17:54.340
what one man's distraction
is another man's attention

01:17:54.340 --> 01:17:55.390
kind of thing.

01:17:55.390 --> 01:17:57.730
It actually depends on
the angle we pick up

01:17:57.730 --> 01:18:00.780
before we can say
definitively that that is.

01:18:00.780 --> 01:18:02.170
Yeah.

01:18:02.170 --> 01:18:04.360
And maybe the
philosophers can actually

01:18:04.360 --> 01:18:05.770
finish my thought here.

01:18:05.770 --> 01:18:12.680
But one of Deleuze's
most wonderful pieces

01:18:12.680 --> 01:18:15.460
is when he talks
about monads, and when

01:18:15.460 --> 01:18:16.450
he talks about Leibniz.

01:18:16.450 --> 01:18:22.150
And Deleuze actually uses
that to talk about Proust,

01:18:22.150 --> 01:18:25.000
and says that--

01:18:25.000 --> 01:18:28.860
I actually have
the passage here,

01:18:28.860 --> 01:18:31.890
but I've lost my glasses
because I'm distracted.

01:18:31.890 --> 01:18:33.200
So I probably can't read it.

01:18:33.200 --> 01:18:36.660
But it's an end here.

01:18:36.660 --> 01:18:40.350
So just maybe you
read "For Leibniz"?

01:18:40.350 --> 01:18:42.910
"For Leibniz the upper
floor is the soul,

01:18:42.910 --> 01:18:47.440
or what we might call following
Guattari, the corporeal aspect

01:18:47.440 --> 01:18:48.880
of subjectivity.

01:18:48.880 --> 01:18:51.220
As Deleuze remarks
in an interview,

01:18:51.220 --> 01:18:54.460
'Leibniz's most famous
proposition is that every soul

01:18:54.460 --> 01:18:55.270
or subject--

01:18:55.270 --> 01:18:59.020
monad-- is completely closed,
windowless, and doorless,

01:18:59.020 --> 01:19:02.950
and contains the whole world in
its darkest depths, while also

01:19:02.950 --> 01:19:05.410
illuminating some little
portion of that world,

01:19:05.410 --> 01:19:07.670
each monad a different portion.

01:19:07.670 --> 01:19:11.680
So the world is enfolded in
each soul, but differently,

01:19:11.680 --> 01:19:14.530
because each illuminates
only one little aspect

01:19:14.530 --> 01:19:16.120
of the overall folding.'"

01:19:16.120 --> 01:19:22.500
So I love that passage so
much, because we are monads.

01:19:22.500 --> 01:19:27.030
And so in some
ways our propensity

01:19:27.030 --> 01:19:30.030
is to turn the world inside.

01:19:30.030 --> 01:19:33.180
It comforts us in
some strange way

01:19:33.180 --> 01:19:36.690
to have that little telephone.

01:19:36.690 --> 01:19:40.410
It's a form of not
wanting to leave your bed.

01:19:40.410 --> 01:19:42.210
And I love not leaving my bed.

01:19:42.210 --> 01:19:45.040
So I understand that desire.

01:19:45.040 --> 01:19:49.860
And so if we are monads, there
are certain moments where,

01:19:49.860 --> 01:19:55.230
thanks to Caravaggio, thanks
to a Proust, a window opens,

01:19:55.230 --> 01:19:58.800
and a window opens
to a part of us

01:19:58.800 --> 01:20:02.030
that suddenly we didn't
even know was there.

01:20:02.030 --> 01:20:04.080
And I think so many
of your examples

01:20:04.080 --> 01:20:06.120
is about this double life.

01:20:06.120 --> 01:20:09.060
We live a double
life all the time.

01:20:09.060 --> 01:20:12.010
Our double life is
the life of our past.

01:20:12.010 --> 01:20:15.380
We have so many moments of
our past that we suppress,

01:20:15.380 --> 01:20:16.860
we put in a corner.

01:20:16.860 --> 01:20:18.630
And then suddenly it happens.

01:20:18.630 --> 01:20:19.440
It's there.

01:20:19.440 --> 01:20:22.890
And that part of our life is
just as much a part of us.

01:20:22.890 --> 01:20:26.080
But actually we don't
always access it.

01:20:26.080 --> 01:20:30.210
So we are distracted
because we're only always

01:20:30.210 --> 01:20:33.360
a tiny fraction of who we are.

01:20:33.360 --> 01:20:39.000
And in fact, we're this
hugely complex machine

01:20:39.000 --> 01:20:44.280
that just gets revealed by
chance, by conversations.

01:20:44.280 --> 01:20:52.170
So I feel that our little phone
there tries to get us to buy,

01:20:52.170 --> 01:20:54.720
get us to focus, gets us to--

01:20:54.720 --> 01:20:56.220
it's a commodity.

01:20:56.220 --> 01:20:58.740
It's those things that
are not commodities

01:20:58.740 --> 01:21:03.630
that makes the little monad that
we are into something plural.

01:21:03.630 --> 01:21:04.345
Yeah.

01:21:04.345 --> 01:21:05.740
[INAUDIBLE]

01:21:05.740 --> 01:21:08.991
Could you take the mic,
just this because this--

01:21:08.991 --> 01:21:09.490
yeah.

01:21:09.490 --> 01:21:10.280
Thanks.

01:21:10.280 --> 01:21:10.780
Yeah.

01:21:10.780 --> 01:21:13.090
I also wonder whether
it has anything

01:21:13.090 --> 01:21:18.530
to do with lapsing
from cognition,

01:21:18.530 --> 01:21:20.990
or from the vocabulary
