01:24:29.630 --> 01:24:32.810
So you can read them
on the internet.

01:24:32.810 --> 01:24:37.160
I mean, you can read
them on your machine,

01:24:37.160 --> 01:24:38.180
or you can read them.

01:24:38.180 --> 01:24:42.560
And it's two utterly
different experiences.

01:24:42.560 --> 01:24:46.700
There's a Paul La Farge novel
which I forget the title of it.

01:24:46.700 --> 01:24:50.150
But it's all about
following links.

01:24:50.150 --> 01:24:52.880
And I listened to it on Audible.

01:24:52.880 --> 01:24:56.240
So I missed it completely.

01:24:56.240 --> 01:24:57.470
He teaches with me.

01:24:57.470 --> 01:25:00.020
And I said I really
liked your book.

01:25:00.020 --> 01:25:03.154
And he said, so, what did you
think of all the references

01:25:03.154 --> 01:25:03.945
to our distraction?

01:25:03.945 --> 01:25:07.360
And it's, of course, I
didn't get any of that.

01:25:11.580 --> 01:25:14.210
And John talks
about the whole idea

01:25:14.210 --> 01:25:17.720
of free and direct
discourse, which in some ways

01:25:17.720 --> 01:25:20.180
could be a pathology right now.

01:25:20.180 --> 01:25:24.380
We are free indirect
discourse, right?

01:25:24.380 --> 01:25:28.160
Yeah, but the second question,
I think the immersion

01:25:28.160 --> 01:25:29.520
and the danger of fiction.

01:25:29.520 --> 01:25:30.020
Right.

01:25:30.020 --> 01:25:31.760
But I also take it,
Danielle, you're

01:25:31.760 --> 01:25:33.530
talking about quixotism, right?

01:25:33.530 --> 01:25:36.890
I mean that is the way in
which, sort of Madam Bovary,

01:25:36.890 --> 01:25:39.860
like that quality of--
or the female quixote,

01:25:39.860 --> 01:25:41.970
is an interesting
18th century example

01:25:41.970 --> 01:25:46.250
of that, where people to
whom the world of books

01:25:46.250 --> 01:25:47.510
becomes like real life.

01:25:47.510 --> 01:25:50.510
I mean, I just think, OK, I
will mention Wreck-It Ralph

01:25:50.510 --> 01:25:51.740
for the second time tonight.

01:25:51.740 --> 01:25:54.410
I mean, I think that
so many modern art

01:25:54.410 --> 01:25:56.090
forms are dealing
with that notion

01:25:56.090 --> 01:25:57.920
that we're living
in game spaces.

01:25:57.920 --> 01:26:00.855
I mean, so Wreck-It Ralph
literally lives inside a game.

01:26:00.855 --> 01:26:02.480
But I think one of
the reasons it works

01:26:02.480 --> 01:26:04.970
is the same reason that
Ready Player One works

01:26:04.970 --> 01:26:07.790
for us, which is that
we are constantly

01:26:07.790 --> 01:26:09.830
thinking about the fact
that we have avatars.

01:26:09.830 --> 01:26:12.320
We have a kind of
fully developed

01:26:12.320 --> 01:26:15.680
internet mediated personality.

01:26:15.680 --> 01:26:19.610
Maybe our being isn't there, but
our personality is out there.

01:26:19.610 --> 01:26:20.900
We're doing work out there.

01:26:20.900 --> 01:26:23.240
People fall in love
on the internet.

01:26:23.240 --> 01:26:24.560
And so fine.

01:26:24.560 --> 01:26:28.010
So Second Life itself is kind
of dead as an experiment.

01:26:28.010 --> 01:26:33.830
But the notion that those
kind of virtual worlding,

01:26:33.830 --> 01:26:37.610
that, I mean, I think that
there's so many art works now

01:26:37.610 --> 01:26:42.260
that are responding to
that way in which ourself

01:26:42.260 --> 01:26:43.670
is kind of partially out there.

01:26:47.780 --> 01:26:51.230
What you said reminded me of
a really wonderful experience.

01:26:51.230 --> 01:26:54.980
So I taught this Don
Quixote tutorial,

01:26:54.980 --> 01:26:57.510
and Bard students
are impossible.

01:26:57.510 --> 01:26:59.300
They do theater until midnight.

01:26:59.300 --> 01:27:03.440
So sometimes our tutorial
was from 11:00 PM to 1:00 AM,

01:27:03.440 --> 01:27:05.390
because those were
the only times

01:27:05.390 --> 01:27:07.400
we could all find together.

01:27:07.400 --> 01:27:12.140
And we were talking
about Madame Bovary,

01:27:12.140 --> 01:27:15.050
and the dangers of fiction.

01:27:15.050 --> 01:27:18.380
And one of the
students said to me,

01:27:18.380 --> 01:27:22.220
we are Don Quixotes,
because we inhabit

01:27:22.220 --> 01:27:24.590
the world of virtual reality.

01:27:24.590 --> 01:27:28.250
My brothers and I had
a terrible childhood.

01:27:28.250 --> 01:27:31.040
Our parents were abusive.

01:27:31.040 --> 01:27:37.860
The only place where we actually
had a life was in these games.

01:27:37.860 --> 01:27:38.480
What are they?

01:27:38.480 --> 01:27:40.394
I mean, games, and--

01:27:40.394 --> 01:27:41.810
Well, they're
called [INAUDIBLE]..

01:27:41.810 --> 01:27:42.643
Something like that.

01:27:42.643 --> 01:27:44.900
I don't even know
the terminology.

01:27:44.900 --> 01:27:47.630
But it made me
stop in my tracks,

01:27:47.630 --> 01:27:49.530
because I'm so old-fashioned.

01:27:49.530 --> 01:27:51.720
It's just reading
is the only thing.

01:27:51.720 --> 01:27:54.530
And I actually, no.

01:27:54.530 --> 01:27:58.100
They had this beautiful,
these memories.

01:27:58.100 --> 01:28:02.824
Their memories were
memories of passing,

01:28:02.824 --> 01:28:06.290
doing some dangerous
things that were virtual,

01:28:06.290 --> 01:28:07.490
that were not real.

01:28:07.490 --> 01:28:09.460
Their reality was miserable.

01:28:09.460 --> 01:28:12.200
Their virtual
reality was something

01:28:12.200 --> 01:28:15.110
that they could share,
something they will remember.

01:28:15.110 --> 01:28:18.050
Remember, when he told me.

01:28:18.050 --> 01:28:21.960
He talks to his brother
about this as his childhood.

01:28:21.960 --> 01:28:25.280
So this is such an
incredible thing.

01:28:25.280 --> 01:28:27.320
I was blown away by that.

01:28:27.320 --> 01:28:30.080
And it made me feel
I am so prejudiced.

01:28:30.080 --> 01:28:33.860
These kids have-- you
guys, the youngsters--

01:28:33.860 --> 01:28:37.590
have such rich lives
compared to stodgy me.

01:28:37.590 --> 01:28:38.900
We just had the telephone.

01:28:38.900 --> 01:28:40.541
We just had the telephone.

01:28:40.541 --> 01:28:41.040
Although--

01:28:41.040 --> 01:28:43.430
And you could ask, you could
do the thought experiment,

01:28:43.430 --> 01:28:50.270
if movies had come
after games, what

01:28:50.270 --> 01:28:52.260
would the cultural
reaction to the movies be,

01:28:52.260 --> 01:28:54.470
where it's just like
you're being broadcast at,

01:28:54.470 --> 01:28:56.640
like you're being
brought into that world

01:28:56.640 --> 01:28:59.000
and given that world,
whereas in the game space

01:28:59.000 --> 01:29:01.550
you're playing with it,
and interacting with it?

01:29:01.550 --> 01:29:04.790
And so maybe that would be
the culturally valorized form,

01:29:04.790 --> 01:29:05.590
rather than--

01:29:05.590 --> 01:29:08.830
But of course when
Don Quixote sees

01:29:08.830 --> 01:29:11.450
a puppet show, and he
thinks they're real,

01:29:11.450 --> 01:29:13.550
and he destroys them.

01:29:13.550 --> 01:29:16.760
And then Orson Welles
makes the Don Quixote movie

01:29:16.760 --> 01:29:18.750
which is so great.

01:29:18.750 --> 01:29:22.880
And Orson Welles makes it
as Don Quixote and Sancho

01:29:22.880 --> 01:29:24.260
at the movies.

01:29:24.260 --> 01:29:28.640
And when Don Quixote sees
these characters galloping

01:29:28.640 --> 01:29:32.750
on the screen, he gets up and
destroys the screen-- totally

01:29:32.750 --> 01:29:34.680
destroys the screen.

01:29:34.680 --> 01:29:37.490
And so I don't know.

01:29:37.490 --> 01:29:41.010
Do we live as intensely, and
is it so terrible to live?

01:29:41.010 --> 01:29:42.680
But can I just
answer that question

01:29:42.680 --> 01:29:43.800
in a slightly
different way, too,

01:29:43.800 --> 01:29:44.780
Danielle, which
is that I do think

01:29:44.780 --> 01:29:47.090
there's a ton of novels
nowadays that actually

01:29:47.090 --> 01:29:50.090
do bifurcate the
internet persona

01:29:50.090 --> 01:29:51.420
and the lived experience.

01:29:51.420 --> 01:29:54.110
In other words, there
is a kind of old person

01:29:54.110 --> 01:29:57.660
account of, oh, 19-year-olds
are on Facebook all the time.

01:29:57.660 --> 01:30:00.890
Therefore all their
whole being is bound up

01:30:00.890 --> 01:30:03.710
in their social transactions,
and their badges,

01:30:03.710 --> 01:30:05.060
and all these other things.

01:30:05.060 --> 01:30:09.260
And for example, Sally Rooney,
I really love both Conversations

01:30:09.260 --> 01:30:11.210
with Friends and Normal People.

01:30:11.210 --> 01:30:13.910
And both of those are about
the difference between what

01:30:13.910 --> 01:30:16.970
you appear like in
that persona that's

01:30:16.970 --> 01:30:19.820
out there electronically,
versus the kind of depth

01:30:19.820 --> 01:30:22.580
that you yourself possess, which
is inarticulate and struggling,

01:30:22.580 --> 01:30:25.850
because it's
personal, and it's not

01:30:25.850 --> 01:30:28.732
personality, which is what
gets played out out there.

01:30:28.732 --> 01:30:30.440
In other words, I
think there's probably,

01:30:30.440 --> 01:30:32.023
just like in every
generation, there's

01:30:32.023 --> 01:30:34.040
a range of artistic responses.

01:30:34.040 --> 01:30:37.430
And one of them is to say, well,
there is that electronic space

01:30:37.430 --> 01:30:40.850
there, but then the real me
is kind of hidden down here,

01:30:40.850 --> 01:30:43.550
and likes to be alone.

01:30:43.550 --> 01:30:45.167
Just take a couple
more questions.

01:30:45.167 --> 01:30:45.666
Yeah.

01:30:48.750 --> 01:30:49.880
Thank you so much.

01:30:49.880 --> 01:30:55.890
I would like to explore the
possibility of meditation,

01:30:55.890 --> 01:31:00.130
and granted the reality
and multiple manifestations

01:31:00.130 --> 01:31:02.080
of distraction.

01:31:02.080 --> 01:31:06.610
Now especially preserved with
technology and media, media

01:31:06.610 --> 01:31:11.020
as medium and communication,
but what is also the practice

01:31:11.020 --> 01:31:12.846
and calling of meditation.

01:31:12.846 --> 01:31:17.860
It is in this context your
reflection on presence/absence.

01:31:17.860 --> 01:31:21.160
Now the presence/absence
can be uncultivated,

01:31:21.160 --> 01:31:23.170
or it can be cultivated.

01:31:23.170 --> 01:31:26.710
So what is the pathways
of cultivation of presence

01:31:26.710 --> 01:31:30.160
and absence, and in the
terms of more a reckoning,

01:31:30.160 --> 01:31:32.980
and therefore, whether
it also requires

01:31:32.980 --> 01:31:38.000
a fundamental critique of some
of the assumptions, like monad.

01:31:38.000 --> 01:31:39.970
Now the idea of the
monad is related

01:31:39.970 --> 01:31:42.190
to monotheism in some ways.

01:31:42.190 --> 01:31:47.290
So therefore, how do we embrace
a cross-cultural perspective?

01:31:47.290 --> 01:31:50.630
And looking at the individual,
though [? with windows, ?]

01:31:50.630 --> 01:31:54.190
but not necessarily as monad,
a different configuration

01:31:54.190 --> 01:31:58.420
of the one and the many,
and therefore Heidegger--

01:31:58.420 --> 01:32:02.440
Heidegger's notion of not only
monad, but being in the world--

01:32:02.440 --> 01:32:04.960
despite all problems
with Heidegger,

01:32:04.960 --> 01:32:07.630
how do we cultivate
that modality

01:32:07.630 --> 01:32:10.000
of being with the world?

01:32:10.000 --> 01:32:12.550
Well, of course,
through boredom.

01:32:12.550 --> 01:32:15.880
I mean, the three
stages of boredom

01:32:15.880 --> 01:32:20.920
in his concept of metaphysics,
there's a real training.

01:32:20.920 --> 01:32:25.330
I mean, if one takes Heidegger
seriously about boredom--

01:32:25.330 --> 01:32:30.970
and I did another crazy tutorial
just about boredom for a year.

01:32:30.970 --> 01:32:34.480
We were never
bored, but it really

01:32:34.480 --> 01:32:40.600
is he takes us through the
steps of being able to,

01:32:40.600 --> 01:32:46.720
first of all, understand why
we can't tolerate, for example,

01:32:46.720 --> 01:32:53.290
missing the train, having no
phone, no clock, no timetable.

01:32:53.290 --> 01:32:56.570
We don't know when the
next train is happening.

01:32:56.570 --> 01:33:00.610
How do we actually get
out of that predicament,

01:33:00.610 --> 01:33:05.350
and meditate rather than
have an anxiety attack?

01:33:05.350 --> 01:33:10.340
And so you have to read those
150 pages to get the answer.

01:33:10.340 --> 01:33:14.320
And I recommend it deeply,
even though the consequences

01:33:14.320 --> 01:33:18.410
can be medically severe.

01:33:18.410 --> 01:33:28.240
But I think boredom is, profound
boredom, conscious boredom

01:33:28.240 --> 01:33:32.620
would be our answer
to meditation.

01:33:32.620 --> 01:33:36.550
It's one way of
looking at meditation.

01:33:36.550 --> 01:33:42.010
I don't meditate, but I
try to accept my boredom.

01:33:42.010 --> 01:33:44.740
And I have a tiny, short
answer, but I really

01:33:44.740 --> 01:33:47.140
want Theo Davis to give
it, rather than me,

01:33:47.140 --> 01:33:49.930
even though I know she won't,
because it's about Thoreau,

01:33:49.930 --> 01:33:52.030
which is just to say
that for me Thoreau

01:33:52.030 --> 01:33:55.000
is the way of thinking about
that moment of awareness

01:33:55.000 --> 01:33:55.750
of presence.

01:33:55.750 --> 01:33:57.680
And just I think so
many of his essays,

01:33:57.680 --> 01:34:00.940
including the one "Walking,"
that I quoted briefly there,

01:34:00.940 --> 01:34:05.110
really try to grapple
with a conscious encounter

01:34:05.110 --> 01:34:06.860
with Eastern religions
that he was having.

01:34:06.860 --> 01:34:11.260
But that, right, I
mean, just there's

01:34:11.260 --> 01:34:14.560
so many different ways to
think about what the presence

01:34:14.560 --> 01:34:18.820
of a self that is a non-monadic
self in a natural environment,

01:34:18.820 --> 01:34:21.820
I find those essays
incredibly though provoking.

01:34:21.820 --> 01:34:24.160
Thank you.

01:34:24.160 --> 01:34:26.680
Thank you very much
for both your talks.

01:34:26.680 --> 01:34:30.520
I have to confess that I was
so intrigued by the Frenchness

01:34:30.520 --> 01:34:34.240
attributed to this
distraction-- distraction--

01:34:34.240 --> 01:34:36.250
that while you were
speaking I went down

01:34:36.250 --> 01:34:41.230
an etymological rabbit hole
on my distraction presence

01:34:41.230 --> 01:34:44.800
object to look up
distraction, the [FRENCH]..

01:34:48.250 --> 01:34:53.151
And I learned that it has to
do with separation, or tearing

01:34:53.151 --> 01:34:53.650
away.

01:34:53.650 --> 01:34:55.990
And I thought, oh, well,
you know, distraction, how

01:34:55.990 --> 01:34:57.520
does that work with extraction?

01:34:57.520 --> 01:35:01.030
Because extraction
seems like the function

01:35:01.030 --> 01:35:04.280
or the result of attention, or
the opposite of distraction.

01:35:04.280 --> 01:35:06.930
If you are really attentive, and
you are extracting something--

01:35:06.930 --> 01:35:07.930
[? Like an oar, yeah. ?]

01:35:07.930 --> 01:35:12.190
--an object, which is also
about separation and detachment

01:35:12.190 --> 01:35:13.270
and removal.

01:35:13.270 --> 01:35:15.490
So that was very kind
of perturbing to me,

01:35:15.490 --> 01:35:18.340
because I thought, well, if
you're present and inattentive,

01:35:18.340 --> 01:35:21.370
and that puts you in
a dynamic of removal,

01:35:21.370 --> 01:35:24.160
or if you're distracted,
and that still puts you

01:35:24.160 --> 01:35:30.030
in the state of removal,
is attachment possible?

01:35:30.030 --> 01:35:31.040
There's no there, there.

01:35:31.040 --> 01:35:31.540
Yeah.

01:35:31.540 --> 01:35:35.090
Or are we just doomed to a
state of either being removed

01:35:35.090 --> 01:35:36.830
from the world,
or always removing

01:35:36.830 --> 01:35:38.200
a part of the world from itself?

01:35:41.770 --> 01:35:43.360
That's a beautiful question.

01:35:43.360 --> 01:35:46.750
I am kind of speechless,
because of course there's

01:35:46.750 --> 01:35:49.510
no answer to that.

01:35:49.510 --> 01:35:50.920
But there's a despair.

01:35:50.920 --> 01:35:52.900
There's always been
a despair about it.

01:35:52.900 --> 01:35:56.140
I mean, I think I write
about this in my book.

01:35:56.140 --> 01:35:58.720
I read yours, but I
didn't re-read mine.

01:35:58.720 --> 01:36:03.220
But Jonathan Edwards
doing a real training

01:36:03.220 --> 01:36:07.630
program in order to
not be distracted,

01:36:07.630 --> 01:36:10.900
and how he couldn't
manage to do it.

01:36:10.900 --> 01:36:14.230
I mean, it's like St.
Augustine trying not to eat,

01:36:14.230 --> 01:36:16.090
and the less he
eats the more he's

01:36:16.090 --> 01:36:21.070
obsessed about food,
that there's really,

01:36:21.070 --> 01:36:25.570
if you want this perfect
attentivity, attention,

01:36:25.570 --> 01:36:28.300
you're thinking about
something you desire.

01:36:28.300 --> 01:36:33.290
And you're not actually in
that space of meditation.

01:36:33.290 --> 01:36:37.090
You're actually in
a disembodied moment

01:36:37.090 --> 01:36:41.070
when you're focusing
on the attempt.

01:36:41.070 --> 01:36:44.050
And the etymology
that you're presenting

01:36:44.050 --> 01:36:46.060
is incredibly compelling.

01:36:46.060 --> 01:36:47.740
And the only thought
I have to add

01:36:47.740 --> 01:36:51.160
to that is that from what
I understand about acedia

01:36:51.160 --> 01:36:52.930
in the early days of
the church, that's

01:36:52.930 --> 01:36:54.370
really a form of the problem.

01:36:54.370 --> 01:36:57.450
Because the point
is that the acedia

01:36:57.450 --> 01:37:00.730
comes to monks who
are committed to kind

01:37:00.730 --> 01:37:02.950
of meditating, and
being with the divine,

01:37:02.950 --> 01:37:04.090
or considering the divine.

01:37:04.090 --> 01:37:06.490
They're not doing
intellectual work.

01:37:06.490 --> 01:37:07.481
They're doing work.

01:37:07.481 --> 01:37:09.730
I mean, they're doing thinking
in the orientian sense.

01:37:09.730 --> 01:37:13.000
They're just trying to
think the thinking that

01:37:13.000 --> 01:37:14.380
ravels and unravels.

01:37:14.380 --> 01:37:16.220
And the danger is
that when you do that,

01:37:16.220 --> 01:37:20.590
you might attain something close
to a divine, but demons come.

01:37:20.590 --> 01:37:22.690
I mean, the problem of
acedia is demons coming.

01:37:22.690 --> 01:37:24.800
And the demons are
really beautiful.

01:37:24.800 --> 01:37:27.460
So the problem is
that you actually

01:37:27.460 --> 01:37:31.180
have succeeded in conjuring
up something which

01:37:31.180 --> 01:37:35.110
you want to be a divine,
but might be demoniac,

01:37:35.110 --> 01:37:36.610
because you've gone astray.

01:37:36.610 --> 01:37:39.110
And they couldn't get out that.

01:37:39.110 --> 01:37:41.500
And I think, as I understand
it, Augustine's solution

01:37:41.500 --> 01:37:44.050
is basically
[? consentobitism. ?]

01:37:44.050 --> 01:37:47.080
In other words, you can't
be monadic as a monk.

01:37:47.080 --> 01:37:48.520
You have to be cenobitic.

01:37:48.520 --> 01:37:52.330
So he has these injunctions
about going and eating meals

01:37:52.330 --> 01:37:53.100
together.

01:37:53.100 --> 01:37:54.933
Like that's how you
solve the noonday demon,

